'''Michael Fred Phelps II'''<ref name="TV Guide">{{cite web |title=Michael Phelps |url=https://www.tvguide.com/celebrities/michael-phelps/258249 |work=TV Guide |access-date=July 28, 2012}}</ref> (born June 30, 1985)<ref name=biography.com>{{cite web |url=http://www.biography.com/people/michael-phelps-345192 |title=Michael Phelps Biography: Swimming, Athlete (1985–) |publisher=[[Biography.com]] ([[FYI (TV network)|FYI]] / [[A&E Networks]]) |access-date=November 18, 2015}}</ref> is an American former competitive swimmer. He is the most successful and [[list of multiple Olympic medalists|most decorated Olympian of all time]]<ref>{{cite web |url=https://sports.yahoo.com/news/phelps-30-medals-in-tokyo-i-dont-think-so-225651329.html |title=Michael Phelps: 30 medals in Tokyo? 'I don't think so' |first1=Tanner |last1=Walters |date=August 13, 2016 |publisher=[[Yahoo! Sports]] |access-date=August 14, 2016}}</ref> with a total of 28 medals.<ref>{{cite web |title=Michael Phelps |url=https://www.olympedia.org/athletes/93860 |website=www.olympedia.org |access-date=26 May 2020}}</ref> Phelps also holds the all-time records for [[list of multiple Olympic gold medalists#List of most Olympic gold medals over career|Olympic gold medals]] (23),<ref name="sportscafe">{{Cite web |url=https://sportscafe.in/articles/sports/2016/aug/12/rio-2016-simone-biles-dazzles-while-phelps-wins-his-22-nd-gold-on-day-6 |title=Rio 2016 {{!}} Simone Biles dazzles while Phelps wins his 22nd gold on day 6|date=August 12, 2016|access-date=August 12, 2016}}</ref> [[List of multiple Olympic gold medalists#List of most career gold medals in individual events|Olympic gold medals in individual events]] (13), and [[List of multiple Olympic medalists#List of most career medals in individual events|Olympic medals in individual events]] (16).<ref>{{cite web |url=https://swimswam.com/phelps-breaks-ties-overall-gold-individual-medals/ |title=Phelps breaks ties for most overall & gold individual medals |first1=Robert |last1=Gibbs |date=August 11, 2016 |publisher=Swimswam |access-date=August 12, 2016}}</ref> When Phelps won eight gold medals at the [[2008 Summer Olympics|2008 Beijing Games]], he broke fellow American swimmer [[Mark Spitz]]'s 1972 record of seven [[List of multiple Olympic gold medalists at a single Games|first-place finishes at any single Olympic Games]]. At the [[2004 Summer Olympics]] in [[Athens]], Phelps already tied the record of eight medals of any color at a single Games by winning six gold and two bronze medals. At the [[2012 Summer Olympics]] in [[London]], Phelps won four gold and two silver medals, and at the [[2016 Summer Olympics]] in [[Rio de Janeiro]], he won five gold medals and one silver. This made him the [[Lists of Olympic medalists#Medalist with most medals by Olympiad|most successful]] athlete of the Games for the fourth Olympics in a row.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://swimswam.com/phelps-named-usocs-male-athlete-rio-olympics/ |title=Phelps named USOC's male athlete of the Rio Olympics |first1=Jared |last1=Anderson |date=September 28, 2016 |publisher=Swimswam |access-date=October 2, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.swimnews.com/News/view/9743 |title=Franklin Pips Phelps For Top Honour |publisher=SwimNews |date=September 16, 2012 |last=Lord |first=Craig |access-date=October 7, 2014 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141006130751/http://www.swimnews.com/News/view/9743 |archive-date=October 6, 2014}}</ref>

Phelps is the [[Olympic-size swimming pool|long course]] world record holder in the men's [[World record progression 400 metres individual medley|400-meter individual medley]] as well as the former long course world record holder in the [[World record progression 200 metres freestyle|200-meter freestyle]], [[World record progression 100 metres butterfly|100-meter butterfly]], [[World record progression 200 metres butterfly|200-meter butterfly]], and [[World record progression 200 metres individual medley|200-meter individual medley]]. He has won 82 medals in major international long course competitions, of which 65 were gold, 14 silver, and three bronze, spanning the Olympics, the [[FINA World Aquatics Championships|World Championships]], and the [[Pan Pacific Swimming Championships|Pan Pacific Championships]]. Phelps's international titles and record-breaking performances have earned him the [[Swimming World Swimmers of the Year|World Swimmer of the Year Award]] eight times and [[Swimming World Swimmers of the Year#American Swimmer of the Year|American Swimmer of the Year Award]] eleven times, as well as the [[List of FINA Athletes of the Year#Swimming|FINA Swimmer of the Year]] Award in 2012 and 2016. Phelps earned ''[[Sports Illustrated]]'' magazine's [[Sportsman of the Year]] award due to his unprecedented Olympic success in the 2008 Games.

After the 2008 Summer Olympics, Phelps started the [[Michael Phelps Foundation]], which focuses on growing the sport of swimming and promoting healthier lifestyles. Phelps retired following the 2012 Olympics, but he made a comeback in April 2014.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.nbcwashington.com/news/local/Olympic-Great-Michael-Phelps-Ending-Retirement-255182961.html |title=Olympic Great Michael Phelps Ending Retirement |access-date=November 21, 2015 |last=Harris |first=Beth |date=April 14, 2014 |publisher=[[WRC-TV|NBC Washington]]}}</ref> At the [[2016 Summer Olympics]] in Rio de Janeiro,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://olympics.nbcsports.com/2016/05/03/michael-phelps-atlanta-swim-meet-olympic-trials/ |title=Michael Phelps left with one meet before Olympic Trials |first1=Nick |last1=Zaccardi |date=May 3, 2016 |publisher=[[Olympics on NBC]] |access-date=May 23, 2016}}</ref> his fifth Olympics, he was selected by his team to be the [[List of flag bearers for the United States at the Olympics|flag bearer of the United States]] at the [[2016 Summer Olympics Parade of Nations]]. He announced his second retirement on August 12, 2016,<ref>{{cite web|last1=Rogers|first1=Martin|title=Michael Phelps on Olympic future: 'I am not coming back in four years'|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/sports/olympics/rio-2016/2016/08/12/michael-phelps-swimming-future-2020-tokyo-olympics/88649590/|website=USA Today|access-date=July 26, 2017}}</ref> having won more medals than 161 countries. He is widely regarded as the greatest swimmer of all time and is often considered to be one of the greatest athletes of all time.<ref>{{cite web|title=Where Does Michael Phelps Rank Among Great Athletes Of All Time?|url=https://bleacherreport.com/articles/49420-where-does-michael-phelps-rank-among-great-athletes-of-all-time|website=BleacherReport|access-date=August 7, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Jones|first1=Tom|title=Jones: Put Michael Phelps in talk about greatest athlete of all time|url=https://www.tampabay.com/sports/olympics/jones-put-michael-phelps-in-talk-about-greatest-athlete-of-all-time/2289455/|website=Tampa Bay Times|access-date=August 7, 2020}}</ref>
{{TOC limit}}

==Early life==

Phelps was born in [[Baltimore, Maryland]],<ref name=biography.com /> and raised in the [[Rodgers Forge]] neighborhood of nearby [[Towson, Maryland|Towson]].<ref name="voyage">{{cite web |title=Phelps' voyage |url=http://www.baltimoresun.com/sports/olympics/bal-te.sp.phelps03aug03,0,5792765.story |work=The Baltimore Sun |date=August 3, 2008 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110629160157/http://www.baltimoresun.com/sports/olympics/bal-te.sp.phelps03aug03,0,5792765.story |archive-date=June 29, 2011 |access-date=September 5, 2010 |url-status=dead  }}</ref> He attended Rodgers Forge Elementary, [[Dumbarton Middle School]], and [[Towson High School]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://ifollosports.com/ifollo-blogs/jon-rapoport/michael-phelps'-baltimore-life-out-pool-photos |title=Michael Phelps' Baltimore Life, In & Out of the Pool (Photos) |author=Jon Rapoport |publisher=ifollosports |date=August 3, 2012 |access-date=August 1, 2014}}</ref> Phelps is the youngest of three children. His mother, Deborah Sue "Debbie" Phelps (''née'' Davisson), is a middle school principal.<ref name="Phelps, ''Beneath the Surface'', p. 15."/> His father, Michael Fred Phelps, is a retired [[Maryland State Police|Maryland State Trooper]] who played [[American football|football]] in high school and college and tried out for the [[Washington Football Team]] in the 1970s.<ref name="Phelps, ''Beneath the Surface'', p. 15.">Phelps, ''Beneath the Surface'', p. 15.</ref><ref name=sun2001>{{cite news |title=Life in the Fast Lane |url=http://www.baltimoresun.com/sports/olympics/bal-phelps0609,0,6686072,full.story |work=[[The Baltimore Sun]] |date=January 14, 2001 |access-date=July 31, 2012 |author=Hiaasen, Rob |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131203010609/http://www.baltimoresun.com/sports/olympics/bal-phelps0609,0,6686072,full.story |archive-date=December 3, 2013  }}</ref> Phelps is of English, German, Irish, Scottish, and Welsh descent.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://freepages.genealogy.rootsweb.ancestry.com/~battle/olympics08/phelps.htm |title=michael phelps |publisher=Freepages.genealogy.rootsweb.ancestry.com |access-date=August 1, 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120808192320/http://freepages.genealogy.rootsweb.ancestry.com/~battle/olympics08/phelps.htm |archive-date=August 8, 2012 |url-status=dead  }}</ref> His parents divorced in 1994 when he was nine years old, and his father remarried in 2000.<ref name=sun2001/> Phelps later revealed that the divorce had a severe negative impact on him and his siblings, and his relationship with his father was distant for a few years after the divorce.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=rmse3WzHmckC|title=Beneath the Surface: My Story|last1=Phelps|first1=Michael|last2=Cazeneuve|first2=Brian|date=August 14, 2012|publisher=Skyhorse Publishing, Inc.|isbn=9781613213247|language=en}}</ref> He graduated from Towson High School in 2003.<ref name="Towson High">{{cite news |last=Klingaman |first=Mike |title=Towson High proud to have its own star in Phelps |url=http://articles.baltimoresun.com/2007-03-31/sports/0703310085_1_michael-phelps-towson-high-kimmie-meissner |access-date=July 28, 2012 |newspaper=The Baltimore Sun |date=May 31, 2007}}</ref>

Phelps began swimming at the age of seven, partly because of the influence of his sisters and partly to provide him with an outlet for his energy.<ref>Phelps, ''Beneath the Surface'', p. 16.</ref> After retirement in 2016, he stated "The only reason I ever got in the water was my mom wanted me to just learn how to swim. My sisters and myself fell in love with the sport, and we decided to swim."<ref>[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=GBgx5Qrgapk&t=220 Michael Phelps explains to Jimmy Fallon that his focus in retirement will be on water safety, to help reduce the number of accidental drownings of children] "Michael Phelps Retires to Run His Baby Boomer's Instagram", The Tonight Show Starring Jimmy Fallon, Thursday, September 1, 2016 (uploaded Sep2)</ref> When Phelps was in the sixth grade, he was diagnosed with [[attention deficit hyperactivity disorder]] (ADHD).<ref>Phelps, ''Beneath the Surface'', p. 24.</ref><ref>Schaller, p. 4.</ref> By the age of 10, he held a national record for his age group (in the 100-meter butterfly)<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.swimmingworldmagazine.com/news/carson-foster-downs-michael-phelps-u-s-national-age-group-record/ |title=Carson Foster Downs Michael Phelps U.S. National Age Group Record |date=July 22, 2012 |work=[[Swimming World]] |access-date=August 6, 2016}}</ref> and began to train at the [[North Baltimore Aquatic Club]] under coach [[Bob Bowman (coach)|Bob Bowman]]. More age group records followed, and as of August 21, 2018, Phelps still held 11 age group records, eight in long course,<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.usaswimming.org/docs/default-source/timesdocuments/relay-records/usa-swimming-national-a-g-records-l-c-3 |title=USA Swimming National Age Group Records Long Course |date=August 31, 2018 |publisher=[[USA Swimming]] |access-date=September 11, 2018}}</ref> and three in short course.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.usaswimming.org/docs/default-source/timesdocuments/relay-records/usa-swimming-national-a-g-records-sc |title=USA Swimming National Age Group Records Short Course |date=August 31, 2018 |publisher=[[USA Swimming]] |access-date=September 11, 2018 }}</ref>

==Career==

===2000 Summer Olympics===
Phelps's rapid improvement culminated when he [[2000 United States Olympic Trials (swimming)|qualified]] for the [[Swimming at the 2000 Summer Olympics|2000 Summer Olympics]] at the age of 15, as he became the youngest male (since [[Ralph Flanagan (swimmer)|Ralph Flanagan]] in 1932) to make a U.S. Olympic swim team in 68 years.<ref>Phelps, ''Beneath the Surface'', p. 85.</ref> While he did not win a medal, he did make the finals and finished fifth in the [[Swimming at the 2000 Summer Olympics – Men's 200 metre butterfly|200-meter butterfly]].<ref>Phelps, ''Beneath the Surface'', p. 78.</ref>

===2001 World championships===
{{MedalTableTop|name=no|header=[[Swimming at the 2001 World Aquatics Championships|2001 World Championships]]}}
{{MedalGold | [[Swimming at the 2001 World Aquatics Championships – Men's 200 metre butterfly|200 m butterfly]] | 1:54.58 (WR)}}
{{MedalBottom}}

At the World Championship Trials for the [[2001 World Aquatics Championships]], on March 30, Phelps broke the world record in the 200-meter butterfly to become, at 15 years and 9 months, the youngest male ever to set a world record in swimming. Previously the youngest male had been [[Ian Thorpe]], who captured the 400-meter freestyle world record at 16 years, 10 months.<ref>Phelps, ''Beneath the Surface'', p. 88.</ref> At the World Championships in Fukuoka, Japan, Phelps broke his own world record in the 200-meter butterfly while en route to become a world champion for the first time.<ref>Phelps, ''Beneath the Surface'', p. 92.</ref>

===2002 Pan Pacific championships===
[[File:Michael_Phelps_2002.jpg|thumb|left|upright|Phelps in 2002]]
{{MedalTableTop|name=no|header=[[2002 Pan Pacific Swimming Championships|2002 Pan Pacific Championships]]}}
{{MedalGold | [[2002 Pan Pacific Swimming Championships – Men's 200 metre individual medley|200 m medley]] | 1:59.70}}
{{MedalGold | [[2002 Pan Pacific Swimming Championships – Men's 400 metre individual medley|400 m medley]] | 4:12.48}}
{{MedalGold | [[2002 Pan Pacific Swimming Championships – Men's 4 × 100 metre medley relay|4×100 m medley]] | 3:33.48 (WR)}}
{{MedalSilver | [[2002 Pan Pacific Swimming Championships – Men's 200 metre butterfly|200 m butterfly]] | 1.55.41}}
{{MedalSilver | [[2002 Pan Pacific Swimming Championships – Men's 4 × 200 metre freestyle relay|4×200 m freestyle]] | 7:11.81}}
{{MedalBottom}}

At Nationals, the selection meet for the [[2002 Pan Pacific Swimming Championships]], in Fort Lauderdale, Florida, Phelps set an American record in the 200-meter individual medley and was just off the world record in the 200-meter butterfly.<ref>Phelps, ''Beneath the Surface'', p. 109.</ref> In the 400-meter individual medley, Phelps bettered the world record held by [[Tom Dolan]] with a time of 4:11.09, just ahead of [[Erik Vendt]], who finished second with a time of 4:11.27, also below the old world record. In the 200-meter freestyle, Phelps was barely beaten by [[Klete Keller]] and in the 100-meter butterfly, Phelps beat [[Ian Crocker]].<ref name="Phelps, ''Beneath the Surface'', p. 110">Phelps, ''Beneath the Surface'', p. 110</ref>

At the 2002 Pan Pacific Swimming Championships in Yokohama, Japan, Phelps won three gold medals and two silvers. In his first event, the 400-meter individual medley, Phelps won gold ahead of [[Erik Vendt]] with a time of 4:12.48. In the 200-meter butterfly, Phelps lost to [[Tom Malchow]], finishing behind him 1:55.41 to 1:55.21. Phelps said he lost because he did not take butterfly training seriously after he broke the world record. In the 200-meter individual medley, Phelps won with a time of 1:59.70. In the 4×200-meter freestyle relay, Phelps, along with [[Nate Dusing]], Klete Keller, and [[Chad Carvin]], won the silver medal with a time 7:11.81 finishing behind Australia. The U.S. 4×100-meter medley relay team consisted of [[Aaron Peirsol]], [[Brendan Hansen]], Phelps, and Ian Crocker. In the final for the medley relay, Phelps swam a 51.1 split, at the time the fastest split in history. The final time of 3:33.48 was a world record.<ref name="Phelps, ''Beneath the Surface'', p. 111">Phelps, ''Beneath the Surface'', p. 111</ref>

===2003 World championships===
{{MedalTableTop|name=no|header=[[Swimming at the 2003 World Aquatics Championships|2003 World Championships]]}}
{{MedalGold | [[Swimming at the 2003 World Aquatics Championships – Men's 200 metre butterfly|200 m butterfly]] | 1:54.35}}
{{MedalGold | [[Swimming at the 2003 World Aquatics Championships – Men's 200 metre individual medley|200 m medley]] | 1:56.04 (WR)}}
{{MedalGold | [[Swimming at the 2003 World Aquatics Championships – Men's 400 metre individual medley|400 m medley]] | 4:09.09 (WR)}}
{{MedalGold | [[Swimming at the 2003 World Aquatics Championships – Men's 4 × 100 metre medley relay|4×100 m medley]] | 3:31.54 (WR) (Phelps swam in heats only)}}
{{MedalSilver | [[Swimming at the 2003 World Aquatics Championships – Men's 100 metre butterfly|100 m butterfly]] | 51.10}}
{{MedalSilver | [[Swimming at the 2003 World Aquatics Championships – Men's 4 × 200 metre freestyle relay|4×200 m freestyle]] | 7:10.26}}
{{MedalBottom}}

At Nationals, Phelps won the 200-meter freestyle, 200-meter backstroke, and the 100-meter butterfly.<ref name="Phelps, ''Beneath the Surface'', p. 122.">Phelps, ''Beneath the Surface'', p. 122.</ref> He became the first American swimmer to win three different races in three different strokes at a national championship.<ref name="Phelps, ''Beneath the Surface'', p. 122."/> At the 2003 Duel in the Pool, a meet that pits swimming stars from Australia and the United States, Phelps broke the world record in the 400-meter individual medley with a time of 4:10.73 and almost broke the world record in the 100-meter butterfly, just missing the record by 0.03 seconds.<ref>Phelps, ''Beneath the Surface'', p. 123.</ref> At a meet in Santa Clara County, California, Phelps broke the world record in the 200-meter individual medley with a time of 1:57.94.<ref>Phelps, ''Beneath the Surface'', p. 134.</ref> Phelps said he broke the 200-meter individual medley world record after [[Don Talbot]] said Phelps was unproven, using his words as motivation.<ref>Phelps, ''Beneath the Surface'', p. 133.</ref>

At the [[2003 World Aquatics Championships]], Phelps won four gold medals, two silver medals, and broke five world records.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.cbc.ca/sports/story/2003/07/27/phelps030727.html |access-date=September 6, 2009 |title=Phelps breaks fifth record at aquatic worlds |publisher=Canadian Broadcasting Corporation |date=July 28, 2003}}</ref> Phelps broke his first world record on July 22 in the semi-finals for the 200-meter butterfly. Phelps swam a 1:53.93 to break his own world record of 1:54.58 set in 2001 and became the first man to swim under 1:54.00.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.omegatiming.com/File/Download?id=000103050026000000FFFFFFFFFFFF01 |title=2003 World Championships – Men's 200 m butterfly results (semi-final) |publisher=Omega Timing |access-date=July 28, 2016}}</ref> In the final of the 200-meter butterfly, on July 23, Phelps easily won the gold medal, but did not come close to his world record with a time of 1:54.35.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.omegatiming.com/File/Download?id=000103050031000000FFFFFFFFFFFF01 |title=2003 World Championships – Men's 200 m butterfly results (final) |publisher=Omega Timing |access-date=July 28, 2016}}</ref> Less than an hour later, Phelps swam the lead-off leg for the 4×200-meter freestyle relay. Phelps put up a solid time of 1:46.60 (an American record) but the Americans could not match the depth of the Australians and ultimately finished second 7:10.26 to 7:08.58.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.omegatiming.com/File/Download?id=000103050034000000FFFFFFFFFFFF01 |title=2003 World Championships – Men's 4×200 m freestyle relay results (final) |publisher=Omega Timing |access-date=July 28, 2016}}</ref> In the 200-meter individual medley, Phelps dominated. On July 24, in the semi-finals of the 200-meter individual medley, he broke his own world record with a time of 1:57.52.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.omegatiming.com/File/Download?id=000103050042000000FFFFFFFFFFFF01 |title=2003 World Championships – Men's 200 m individual medley results (semi-final) |publisher=Omega Timing |access-date=July 28, 2016}}</ref> On July 25, in the final of the 200-meter individual medley, Phelps smashed his own record with a time of 1:56.04 to win the gold medal and finished almost 3 seconds ahead of [[Ian Thorpe]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.omegatiming.com/File/Download?id=000103050053000000FFFFFFFFFFFF01 |title=2003 World Championships – Men's 200 m individual medley results (final) |publisher=Omega Timing |access-date=July 28, 2016}}</ref> About an hour before the final of the 200-meter individual medley, Phelps swam in the semi-finals of the 100-meter butterfly. Phelps dominated again, finishing in the top seed position with a world record time of 51.47.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.omegatiming.com/File/Download?id=00010305004F000000FFFFFFFFFFFF01 |title=2003 World Championships – Men's 100 m butterfly results (semi-final) |publisher=Omega Timing |access-date=July 28, 2016}}</ref> However, in the final of the 100-meter butterfly, on July 26, [[Ian Crocker]] erased Phelps's world record with a time of 50.98, to become the first man under 51 seconds. Phelps swam a 51.10 (also under his former world record), but had to settle for silver.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.omegatiming.com/File/Download?id=000103050060000000FFFFFFFFFFFF01 |title=2003 World Championships – Men's 100 m butterfly results (final) |publisher=Omega Timing |access-date=July 28, 2016}}</ref> In the final of the 400-meter individual medley, on July 27, Phelps broke his own world record with a time of 4:09.09 to easily claim the gold medal.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.omegatiming.com/File/Download?id=000103050069000000FFFFFFFFFFFF01 |title=2003 World Championships – Men's 400 m individual medley results (final) |publisher=Omega Timing |access-date=July 28, 2016}}</ref> About half an hour later, Phelps earned his final gold medal when the United States team won the 4×100-meter medley relay.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.omegatiming.com/File/Download?id=00010305006B000000FFFFFFFFFFFF01 |title=2003 World Championships – Men's 4×100 m medley relay results (final) |publisher=Omega Timing |access-date=July 28, 2016}}</ref> Phelps did not swim in the finals, but still earned a medal because he swam in the heats.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.omegatiming.com/File/Download?id=000103050064000000FFFFFFFFFFFF00 |title=2003 World Championships – Men's 4×100 m medley relay results (heats) |publisher=Omega Timing |access-date=July 28, 2016}}</ref>

===2004 Summer Olympics===

====Trials====
At the [[2004 United States Olympic Trials (swimming)|2004 U.S. Olympic Team Trials]], Phelps competed in six events; the 200- and 400-meter individual medley, the 100- and 200-meter butterfly, the 200-meter freestyle, and the 200-meter backstroke.<ref>Phelps, ''Beneath the Surface'', p. 179.</ref> In his first event, the 400-meter individual medley, Phelps easily won with a world record time of 4:08.41.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://omegatiming.com/File/Download?id=000104090005000000FFFFFFFFFFFF01 |title=2004 U.S. Olympic Team Trials – Men's 400 m individual medley results (final) |publisher=Omega Timing |access-date=August 2, 2016}}</ref> Two days later, in the 200-meter freestyle, Phelps won with a time of 1:46.27, finishing sixth-tenths of a second ahead of [[Klete Keller]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://omegatiming.com/File/Download?id=00010409001A000000FFFFFFFFFFFF01 |title=2004 U.S. Olympic Team Trials – Men's 200 m freestyle results (final) |publisher=Omega Timing |access-date=August 2, 2016}}</ref> Phelps, however, was not pleased with the result and wanted to be in the 1:45s and was uncertain if he would swim the event in Athens.<ref>Phelps, ''Beneath the Surface'', p. 181.</ref> The following day, Phelps won in the 200-meter butterfly with a time of 1:54.31, three seconds ahead of second-place finisher [[Tom Malchow]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://omegatiming.com/File/Download?id=000104090025000000FFFFFFFFFFFF01 |title=2004 U.S. Olympic Team Trials – Men's 200 m butterfly results (final) |publisher=Omega Timing |access-date=August 2, 2016}}</ref> After two days off, Phelps was back in the pool and finished second to [[Aaron Peirsol]] (who broke the world record) in the 200-meter backstroke.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://omegatiming.com/File/Download?id=00010409003B000000FFFFFFFFFFFF01 |title=2004 U.S. Olympic Team Trials – Men's 200 m backstroke results (final) |publisher=Omega Timing |access-date=August 2, 2016}}</ref> Less than half an hour later, Phelps won the 200-meter individual medley title ahead of [[Ryan Lochte]] by 2.70 seconds.<ref>Phelps, ''Beneath the Surface'', p. 184.</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://omegatiming.com/File/Download?id=00010409003D000000FFFFFFFFFFFF01 |title=2004 U.S. Olympic Team Trials – Men's 200 m individual medley results (final) |publisher=Omega Timing |access-date=August 2, 2016}}</ref> The following day, Phelps finished second to [[Ian Crocker]] in the 100-meter butterfly. Crocker won in a time of 50.76, a world record and 0.39 seconds ahead of Phelps.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://omegatiming.com/File/Download?id=000104090043000000FFFFFFFFFFFF01 |title=2004 U.S. Olympic Team Trials – Men's 100 m butterfly results (final) |publisher=Omega Timing |access-date=August 2, 2016}}</ref> When the Trials were over, Phelps became the first person to qualify in six individual events for a U.S. Olympic team.<ref name="Phelps, ''Beneath the Surface'', p. 186.">Phelps, ''Beneath the Surface'', p. 186.</ref> However, Phelps dropped the 200-meter backstroke to focus on the 200-meter freestyle because he wanted to race [[Ian Thorpe]].<ref name="Phelps, ''Beneath the Surface'', p. 186."/> Even though Phelps did not compete in the 100-meter freestyle at the Trials, he was still selected for the 4×100-meter freestyle relay. [[Gary Hall, Jr.]] thought this was unfair and said Phelps did not deserve a spot on the relay. Phelps argued his program was too crowded to compete in 100-meter freestyle and was at least among the top four swimmers because he had beaten the top-seeded [[Jason Lezak]] the last time he had swum against him.<ref>Phelps, ''Beneath the Surface'', p. 191.</ref>

{{MedalTableTop|name=no|header=[[Swimming at the 2004 Summer Olympics|2004 Summer Olympics]]}}
{{MedalGold | [[Swimming at the 2004 Summer Olympics – Men's 100 metre butterfly|100 m butterfly]] | 51.25 (OR)}}
{{MedalGold | [[Swimming at the 2004 Summer Olympics – Men's 200 metre butterfly|200 m butterfly]] | 1:54.04 (OR)}}
{{MedalGold | [[Swimming at the 2004 Summer Olympics – Men's 200 metre individual medley|200 m medley]] | 1:57.14 (OR)}}
{{MedalGold | [[Swimming at the 2004 Summer Olympics – Men's 400 metre individual medley|400 m medley]] | 4:08.26 (WR)}}
{{MedalGold | [[Swimming at the 2004 Summer Olympics – Men's 4 × 200 metre freestyle relay|4×200 m freestyle]] | 7:07.33 (NR)}}
{{MedalGold | [[Swimming at the 2004 Summer Olympics – Men's 4 × 100 metre medley relay|4×100 m medley]] | 3:30.68 (WR) (Phelps swam in heats only)}}
{{MedalBronze | [[Swimming at the 2004 Summer Olympics – Men's 200 metre freestyle|200 m freestyle]] | 1:45.32 (NR)}}
{{MedalBronze | [[Swimming at the 2004 Summer Olympics – Men's 4 × 100 metre freestyle relay|4×100 m freestyle]] | 3:14.62}}
{{MedalBottom}}

====Athens====
In his first event, the 400-meter individual medley, Phelps won his first Olympic gold medal in the world record time of 4:08.26.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://omegatiming.com/File/Download?id=000104060006000000FFFFFFFFFFFF01 |title=Games of the XXVIIIth Olympiad – Men's 400 m individual medley results (final) |publisher=Omega Timing |access-date=August 2, 2016}}</ref><ref>Schaller, p. 35.</ref> The following day, Phelps, along with [[Ian Crocker]], [[Neil Walker (swimmer)|Neil Walker]], and Jason Lezak, finished in third place in the 4×100-meter freestyle relay with a time of 3:14.62.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://omegatiming.com/File/Download?id=00010406001B000000FFFFFFFFFFFF01 |title=Games of the XXVIIIth Olympiad – Men's 4×100 m freestyle relay results (final) |publisher=Omega Timing |access-date=August 2, 2016}}</ref><ref>Schaller, p. 36.</ref> Crocker's lead-off time of 50.05 was the worst among the field and was blamed on sickness.<ref>Phelps, ''Beneath the Surface'', p. 202.</ref><ref>Schaller, p. 37.</ref> In the event many were calling ''The Race of the Century'', the 200-meter freestyle that was held the following day, Phelps finished in third place behind [[Ian Thorpe]] and [[Pieter van den Hoogenband]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://omegatiming.com/File/Download?id=000104060020000000FFFFFFFFFFFF01 |title=Games of the XXVIIIth Olympiad – Men's 200 m freestyle results (final) |publisher=Omega Timing |access-date=August 2, 2016}}</ref><ref>Schaller, p. 38.</ref> Although this race ended the chance to match Spitz's record, Phelps had savored the challenge even though it was not his strongest event, saying "How can I be disappointed? I swam in a field with the two fastest freestylers of all time".<ref>Phelps, ''Beneath the Surface'', p. 204.</ref> In his fourth event, the 200-meter butterfly, held the following day, Phelps won a gold medal with a time of 1:54.04, breaking [[Tom Malchow]]'s Olympic record.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://omegatiming.com/File/Download?id=00010406002C000000FFFFFFFFFFFF01 |title=Games of the XXVIIIth Olympiad – Men's 200 m butterfly results (final) |publisher=Omega Timing |access-date=August 2, 2016}}</ref><ref>Schaller, p. 39.</ref> About an hour later, in the 4×200-meter freestyle relay, Phelps, along with [[Ryan Lochte]], [[Peter Vanderkaay]], and [[Klete Keller]], finished in first place with a time of 7:07.33.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://omegatiming.com/File/Download?id=000104060030000000FFFFFFFFFFFF01 |title=Games of the XXVIIIth Olympiad – Men's 4×200 m freestyle relay results (final) |publisher=Omega Timing |access-date=August 2, 2016}}</ref> Two days later, in the 200-meter individual medley, Phelps finished first with a time of 1:57.14, an Olympic record.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://omegatiming.com/File/Download?id=000104060046000000FFFFFFFFFFFF01 |title=Games of the XXVIIIth Olympiad – Men's 200 m individual medley results (final) |publisher=Omega Timing |access-date=August 2, 2016}}</ref> In the 100-meter butterfly final, held the following day, Phelps defeated American teammate [[Ian Crocker]] (who held the world record in the event at the time) by just 0.04 seconds with a time of 51.25.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://omegatiming.com/File/Download?id=00010406004E000000FFFFFFFFFFFF01 |title=Games of the XXVIIIth Olympiad – Men's 100 m butterfly results (final) |publisher=Omega Timing |access-date=August 2, 2016}}</ref><ref name="Schaller, p. 40">Schaller, p. 40.</ref> Traditionally, the American who places highest in an individual event will be automatically given the corresponding leg in the 4×100-meter medley relay final. This gave Phelps an automatic entry into the medley relay, but he deferred and Crocker swam instead.<ref name="Schaller, p. 40"/><ref name="Phelps, ''Beneath the Surface'', p. 218.">Phelps, ''Beneath the Surface'', p. 218.</ref> Phelps's gesture gave Crocker a chance to make amends (for a mistake at the start of a previous race) as well, getting his final shot at a gold medal.<ref name="Phelps, ''Beneath the Surface'', p. 218."/> The American medley team went on to win the event in world-record time, and, since Phelps had raced in a preliminary heat of the medley relay, he was also awarded a gold medal along with the team members who competed in the final.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://omegatiming.com/File/Download?id=00010406004C000000FFFFFFFFFFFF01 |title=Games of the XXVIIIth Olympiad – Men's 4×100 m medley relay results (heats) |publisher=Omega Timing |access-date=August 2, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://omegatiming.com/File/Download?id=000104060055000000FFFFFFFFFFFF01 |title=Games of the XXVIIIth Olympiad – Men's 4×100 m medley relay results (final) |publisher=Omega Timing |access-date=August 2, 2016}}</ref> In winning six gold and two bronze medals, Phelps, still a teenager, had the [[List of multiple Olympic gold medalists at a single Games|second-best performance]] ever at a single Olympics, behind [[Mark Spitz]]'s seven gold medals at the [[1972 Summer Olympics]]. Also, he became the second male swimmer ever to win more than two individual titles at a single Games with four, tying Spitz's four from 1972.

===2005 World championships===
[[File:2005 FINA World Championships - victory lap of the 100 m butterfly.jpg|thumb|left|Victory lap of the 100 m butterfly during the 2005 FINA World Championships in Montréal. Phelps is far right.]]
{{MedalTableTop|name=no|header=[[Swimming at the 2005 World Aquatics Championships|2005 World Aquatics Championships]]}}
{{MedalGold | [[Swimming at the 2005 World Aquatics Championships – Men's 200 metre freestyle|200 m freestyle]] | 1:45.20 (NR)}}
{{MedalGold | [[Swimming at the 2005 World Aquatics Championships – Men's 200 metre individual medley|200 m medley]] | 1:56.68}}
{{MedalGold | [[Swimming at the 2005 World Aquatics Championships – Men's 4 × 100 metre freestyle relay|4×100 m freestyle]] | 3:13.77 (CR)}}
{{MedalGold | [[Swimming at the 2005 World Aquatics Championships – Men's 4 × 200 metre freestyle relay|4×200 m freestyle]] | 7:06.58}}
{{MedalGold | [[Swimming at the 2005 World Aquatics Championships – Men's 4 × 100 metre medley relay|4×100 m medley]] | 3:31.85 (Phelps swam in heats only)}}
{{MedalSilver | [[Swimming at the 2005 World Aquatics Championships – Men's 100 metre butterfly|100 m butterfly]] |51.65}}
{{MedalBottom}}

At the 2005 World Championship Trials, Phelps decided to drop his specialty events, the 400-meter individual medley and the 200-meter butterfly, and experiment with the 400-meter freestyle and the 100-meter freestyle.<ref>Phelps, ''Beneath the Surface'', p. 243.</ref> Phelps went on to win the 400-meter freestyle, the 200-meter freestyle, the 100-meter butterfly, the 100-meter freestyle, and the 200-meter individual medley at the Trials.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.omegatiming.com/File/Download?id=0001050F0008000000FFFFFFFFFFFF01 |title=2005 World Championship Trials – Men's 400 m freestyle results (final) |publisher=Omega Timing |access-date=August 3, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.omegatiming.com/File/Download?id=0001050F0014000000FFFFFFFFFFFF01 |title=2005 World Championship Trials – Men's 200 m freestyle results (final) |publisher=Omega Timing |access-date=August 3, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.omegatiming.com/File/Download?id=0001050F001E000000FFFFFFFFFFFF01 |title=2005 World Championship Trials – Men's 100 m butterfly results (final) |publisher=Omega Timing |access-date=August 3, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.omegatiming.com/File/Download?id=0001050F0028000000FFFFFFFFFFFF01 |title=2005 World Championship Trials – Men's 100 m freestyle results (final) |publisher=Omega Timing |access-date=August 3, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.omegatiming.com/File/Download?id=0001050F002A000000FFFFFFFFFFFF01 |title=2005 World Championship Trials – Men's 200 m individual medley results (final) |publisher=Omega Timing |access-date=August 3, 2016}}</ref>

At the [[2005 World Aquatics Championships]], Phelps won a total of six medals, five golds and one silver.<ref>Schaller, p. 59.</ref> In the 400-meter freestyle, Phelps did not make it past the preliminary heats and finished 18th overall with a time of 3:50.53.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.omegatiming.com/File/Download?id=000105090001000000FFFFFFFFFFFF01 |title=2005 World Championships – Men's 400 m freestyle results (heats) |publisher=Omega Timing |access-date=August 3, 2016}}</ref> Later that day, in the 4×100-meter freestyle relay, Phelps won his first gold in the Championships.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.omegatiming.com/File/Download?id=000105090010000000FFFFFFFFFFFF01 |title=2005 World Championships – Men's 4×100 m freestyle relay results (final) |publisher=Omega Timing |access-date=August 3, 2016}}</ref> Two days later, on July 26, Phelps won his second gold in the 200-meter freestyle with a new American record time of 1:45.20, finishing ahead of [[Grant Hackett]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.omegatiming.com/File/Download?id=000105090029000000FFFFFFFFFFFF01 |title=2005 World Championships – Men's 200 m freestyle results (final) |publisher=Omega Timing |access-date=August 3, 2016}}</ref> Two days later, on July 28, Phelps finished seventh in the 100-meter freestyle final.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.omegatiming.com/File/Download?id=00010509003E000000FFFFFFFFFFFF01 |title=2005 World Championships – Men's 100 m freestyle results (final) |publisher=Omega Timing |access-date=August 3, 2016}}</ref> Later that day, Phelps won his third gold in the 200-meter individual medley.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.omegatiming.com/File/Download?id=000105090042000000FFFFFFFFFFFF01 |title=2005 World Championships – Men's 200 m individual medley results (final) |publisher=Omega Timing |access-date=August 3, 2016}}</ref> On July 29, Phelps, along with [[Ryan Lochte]], [[Peter Vanderkaay]] and [[Klete Keller]], won the gold in the 4×200-meter freestyle relay with a time of 7:06.58. This was the fourth gold medal for Phelps.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.omegatiming.com/File/Download?id=000105090054000000FFFFFFFFFFFF01 |title=2005 World Championships – Men's 4×200 m freestyle relay results (final) |publisher=Omega Timing |access-date=August 3, 2016}}</ref> On July 30, Phelps swam in his last individual event, the 100-meter butterfly. In the final, Phelps could not match the speed of [[Ian Crocker]] and had to settle for silver, finishing 51.65 to 50.40, a new world record for Crocker.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.omegatiming.com/File/Download?id=00010509005D000000FFFFFFFFFFFF01 |title=2005 World Championships – Men's 100 m butterfly results (final) |publisher=Omega Timing |access-date=August 3, 2016}}</ref> On July 31, Phelps earned his final gold medal when the United States team won the 4×100-meter medley relay.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.omegatiming.com/File/Download?id=00010509006C000000FFFFFFFFFFFF01 |title=2005 World Championships – Men's 4×100 m medley relay results (final) |publisher=Omega Timing |access-date=August 3, 2016}}</ref> Phelps did not swim in the finals but still earned a medal because he swam in the heats.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.omegatiming.com/File/Download?id=000105090065000000FFFFFFFFFFFF01 |title=2005 World Championships – Men's 4×100 m medley relay results (heats) |publisher=Omega Timing |access-date=August 3, 2016}}</ref>

===2006 Pan Pacific championships===
{{MedalTableTop|name=no|header=[[2006 Pan Pacific Swimming Championships|2006 Pan Pacific Championships]]}}
{{MedalGold | [[2006 Pan Pacific Swimming Championships – Men's 200 metre butterfly|200 m butterfly]] | 1:53.80 (WR)}}
{{MedalGold | [[2006 Pan Pacific Swimming Championships – Men's 200 metre individual medley|200 m medley]] | 1:55.84 (WR)}}
{{MedalGold | [[2006 Pan Pacific Swimming Championships – Men's 400 metre individual medley|400 m medley]] | 4:10.47 (CR)}}
{{MedalGold | [[2006 Pan Pacific Swimming Championships – Men's 4 × 100 metre freestyle relay|4×100 m freestyle]] | 3:12.46 (WR)}}
{{MedalGold | [[2006 Pan Pacific Swimming Championships – Men's 4 × 200 metre freestyle relay|4×200 m freestyle]] | 7:05.28 (CR)}}
{{MedalSilver | [[2006 Pan Pacific Swimming Championships – Men's 200 metre backstroke|200 m backstroke]] | 1:56.81}}
{{MedalBottom}}

At the 2006 National Championships, Phelps won three events.<ref>Phelps, ''Beneath the Surface'', p. 261.</ref> In his first event, the 200-meter butterfly, Phelps won with a championship record of 1:54.32.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://omegatiming.com/File/Download?id=000106070016000000FFFFFFFFFFFF01 |title=2006 ConocoPhillips National Championships – Men's 200 m butterfly results (final) |publisher=Omega Timing |access-date=August 3, 2016}}</ref> In his second event, the 100-meter butterfly, Phelps just edged out [[Ian Crocker]] 51.51 (another championship record) to 51.73.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://omegatiming.com/File/Download?id=000106070020000000FFFFFFFFFFFF01 |title=2006 ConocoPhillips National Championships – Men's 100 m butterfly results (final) |publisher=Omega Timing |access-date=August 3, 2016}}</ref> In his third event, the 200-meter individual medley, Phelps won with a time of 1:56.50, just ahead of [[Ryan Lochte]]'s time of 1:56.78.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://omegatiming.com/File/Download?id=00010607002D000000FFFFFFFFFFFF01 |title=2006 ConocoPhillips National Championships – Men's 200 m individual medley results (final) |publisher=Omega Timing |access-date=August 3, 2016}}</ref>

At the [[2006 Pan Pacific Swimming Championships]] in Victoria, British Columbia, Phelps won five gold medals and one silver.<ref>Phelps, ''Beneath the Surface'', p. 264.</ref> In his first event, the 200-meter butterfly, Phelps won in a world record time of 1:53.80, his first world record in two years.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.omegatiming.com/File/Download?id=00010605000E000000FFFFFFFFFFFF01 |title=2006 Pan Pacific Swimming Championships – Men's 200 m butterfly results (final) |publisher=Omega Timing |access-date=August 4, 2016}}</ref> In his second event, the 400-meter individual medley, Phelps easily won with a time of 4:10.47, 3.38 seconds ahead of second-place finisher [[Robert Margalis]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.omegatiming.com/File/Download?id=00010605001C000000FFFFFFFFFFFF01 |title=2006 Pan Pacific Swimming Championships – Men's 400 m individual medley results (final) |access-date=August 4, 2016}}</ref> In his third event, the 4×200-meter freestyle relay, Phelps, along with [[Ryan Lochte]], [[Peter Vanderkaay]], and [[Klete Keller]], won the gold medal with a time of 7:05.28.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.omegatiming.com/File/Download?id=00010605001E000000FFFFFFFFFFFF01 |title=2006 Pan Pacific Swimming Championships – Men's 4×200 m freestyle relay results (final) |publisher=Omega Timing |access-date=August 4, 2016}}</ref> In his fourth event, the 200-meter backstroke, Phelps won the silver medal, finishing behind [[Aaron Peirsol]] 1:56.81 to 1:54.44 (a new world record).<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.omegatiming.com/File/Download?id=00010605002A000000FFFFFFFFFFFF01 |title=2006 Pan Pacific Swimming Championships – Men's 200 m backstroke results (final) |publisher=Omega Timing |access-date=August 4, 2016}}</ref> In his fifth event, the 4×100-meter freestyle relay, Phelps, along with [[Neil Walker (swimmer)|Neil Walker]], [[Cullen Jones]], and Jason Lezak, won the gold medal with a world-record time 3:12.46.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.omegatiming.com/File/Download?id=00010605002C000000FFFFFFFFFFFF01 |title=2006 Pan Pacific Swimming Championships – Men's 4×100 m freestyle relay results (final) |publisher=Omega Timing |access-date=August 4, 2016}}</ref> In his sixth event, the 200-meter individual medley, Phelps won with a world record time of 1:55.84, breaking his record of 1:55.94 set in 2003.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.omegatiming.com/File/Download?id=000106050037000000FFFFFFFFFFFF01 |title=2006 Pan Pacific Swimming Championships – Men's 200 m individual medley results (final) |publisher=Omega Timing |access-date=August 4, 2016}}</ref>

===2007 World championships===
{{MedalTableTop|name=no|header=[[Swimming at the 2007 World Aquatics Championships|2007 World Championships]]}}
{{MedalGold | [[Swimming at the 2007 World Aquatics Championships – Men's 200 metre freestyle|200 m freestyle]] | 1:43.86 (WR)}}
{{MedalGold | [[Swimming at the 2007 World Aquatics Championships – Men's 100 metre butterfly|100 m butterfly]] | 50.77}}
{{MedalGold | [[Swimming at the 2007 World Aquatics Championships – Men's 200 metre butterfly|200 m butterfly]] | 1:52.09 (WR)}}
{{MedalGold | [[Swimming at the 2007 World Aquatics Championships – Men's 200 metre individual medley|200 m medley]] | 1:54.98 (WR)}}
{{MedalGold | [[Swimming at the 2007 World Aquatics Championships – Men's 400 metre individual medley|400 m medley]] | 4:06.22 (WR)}}
{{MedalGold | [[Swimming at the 2007 World Aquatics Championships – Men's 4 × 100 metre freestyle relay|4×100 m freestyle]] | 3:12.72 (CR)}}
{{MedalGold | [[Swimming at the 2007 World Aquatics Championships – Men's 4 × 200 metre freestyle relay|4×200 m freestyle]] | 7:03.24 (WR)}}
{{MedalBottom}}

At the [[2007 World Aquatics Championships]], Phelps won seven gold medals, tying the record for a global long-course championship held by [[Mark Spitz]] since the [[1972 Summer Olympics]], and broke five world records.<ref>Schaller, p. 60.</ref> Phelps first gold medal came in the 4×100-meter freestyle. Phelps swam the lead-off leg in 48.42 seconds and [[Neil Walker (swimmer)|Neil Walker]], [[Cullen Jones]] and Jason Lezak each expanded the lead to win in a Championship record of 3:12.72, just missing the world record of 3:12.46 set the previous year.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.omegatiming.com/File/Download?id=0001070D0010000000FFFFFFFFFFFF01 |title=12th FINA World Championships – Men's 4×100 m freestyle relay results (final) |publisher=Omega Timing |access-date=August 4, 2016}}</ref> His lead-off time was faster than the winning time in the individual 100-meter freestyle final later in the meet. Phelps set his first world record in the Championships in the 200-meter freestyle, his second race. Phelps won the gold ahead of [[Pieter van den Hoogenband]] and broke [[Ian Thorpe]]'s six-year-old world record with a time of 1:43.86.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.omegatiming.com/File/Download?id=0001070D0022000000FFFFFFFFFFFF01 |title=12th FINA World Championships – Men's 200 m freestyle results (final) |publisher=Omega Timing |access-date=August 4, 2016}}</ref> For his third race, the 200-meter butterfly, Phelps won the gold and bettered his own world record of 1:53.71 with a time of 1:52.09.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.omegatiming.com/File/Download?id=0001070D0030000000FFFFFFFFFFFF01 |title=12th FINA World Championships – Men's 200 m butterfly results (final) |publisher=Omega Timing |access-date=August 4, 2016}}</ref> For his fourth race, the 200-meter individual medley, Phelps set his third world record with a time of 1:54.98, bettering his own world-record time of 1:55.84<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.omegatiming.com/File/Download?id=0001070D003C000000FFFFFFFFFFFF01 |title=12th FINA World Championships – Men's 200 m individual medley results (final) |publisher=Omega Timing |access-date=August 4, 2016}}</ref> For his fifth race, the 4×200-meter freestyle relay, Phelps swam the lead-off leg in 1:45.36 as the American team of [[Ryan Lochte]], [[Klete Keller]], and [[Peter Vanderkaay]] went on to win the gold medal and beat the previous world record set by Australia in 2001 with a time 7:03.24.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.omegatiming.com/File/Download?id=0001070D0052000000FFFFFFFFFFFF01 |title=12th FINA World Championships – Men's 4×200 m freestyle relay results (final) |publisher=Omega Timing |access-date=August 4, 2016}}</ref> For his sixth race, the 100-meter butterfly, Phelps edged out [[Ian Crocker]] 50.77 to 50.82 to win his sixth gold medal.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.omegatiming.com/File/Download?id=0001070D005E000000FFFFFFFFFFFF01 |title=12th FINA World Championships – Men's 100 m butterfly results (final) |access-date=August 4, 2016}}</ref> For his seventh event, the 400-meter individual medley, Phelps won the gold medal in a world-record time of 4:06.22, more than 3.5 seconds ahead of [[Ryan Lochte]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.omegatiming.com/File/Download?id=0001070D0068000000FFFFFFFFFFFF01 |title=12th FINA World Championships – Men's 400 m individual medley results (final) |publisher=Omega Timing |access-date=August 4, 2016}}</ref> By winning seven gold medals, Phelps broke the record of six set by [[Ian Thorpe]] at the [[2001 World Aquatics Championships|2001 World Championships]]. The 4×100-meter medley relay team received a disqualification for a false start during a changeover in the heats, ending Phelps's chance of eight gold medals.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.omegatiming.com/File/Download?id=0001070D0065000000FFFFFFFFFFFF01 |title=12th FINA World Championships – 4×100 m medley relay results (heats) |publisher=Omega Timing |access-date=August 4, 2016}}</ref>

Even though Phelps competed in the backstroke in international competition only once (at the [[2006 Pan Pacific Swimming Championships|2006 Pan Pacific Championships]]), he was among the best backstroke swimmers in the world. This is illustrated by his personal best times set in 2007, four months after the World Championships. At the [[United States Swimming National Championships|US Nationals]] in [[Indianapolis]] on August 1, 2007, Phelps swam a 1:54.65 in the 200-meter backstroke, which was the third fastest of all time in the event, 0.33 of a second off the world record of 1:54.32 held by [[Ryan Lochte]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.usaswimming.org/_Rainbow/Documents/58786eab-e330-47a6-8f18-e50e65be34db/men200mbackf.htm |title=Men 200 LC Meter Backstroke |publisher=[[USA Swimming]] |access-date=August 4, 2016}}</ref> Two days later Phelps swam a time of 53.01 sec in the 100-meter backstroke, 0.03 of a second short of the world record of 52.98 held by [[Aaron Peirsol]] and the second-fastest performance of all time.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://edition.cnn.com/2007/SPORT/08/04/swim.phelps.reut/index.html?eref=edition_sport |title=Phelps grabs two titles in an hour |access-date=August 4, 2016}}</ref>
In 2007 Phelps swam into the all-time top three performances in seven individual events, four of these being world records.

