{{MedalBottom}}

At the 2009 National Championships, Phelps drastically shortened his program, swimming in only three individual events. In his first event, the 200-meter freestyle, Phelps won with a time of 1:44.23.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.omegatiming.com/File/Download?id=0001090E0015000000FFFFFFFFFFFF01 |title=2009 National Championships – 200 m freestyle results (final) |publisher=Omega Timing |access-date=August 10, 2016}}</ref> In his second event, the 200-meter butterfly, Phelps easily won with a time of 1:52.76, 0.88 seconds ahead of the second-place finisher.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.omegatiming.com/File/Download?id=0001090E0018000000FFFFFFFFFFFF01 |title=2009 National Championships – 200 m butterfly results (final) |publisher=Omega Timing |access-date=August 10, 2016}}</ref> In his third event, the 100-meter butterfly, Phelps won with a world-record time of 50.22.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.omegatiming.com/File/Download?id=0001090E0022000000FFFFFFFFFFFF01 |title=2009 National Championships – 100 m butterfly results (final) |publisher=Omega Timing |access-date=August 10, 2016}}</ref>
[[File:Michael Phelps before the start of the 200m butterfly semi-final - 2009 FINA World Championships.jpg|thumb|left|Phelps (center) before the start of the 200-meter butterfly semi-final during 2009 FINA World Championships]]
At the [[2009 World Aquatics Championships]], Phelps won a total of 6 medals, 5 golds and 1 silver. In his first event, the 4×100-meter freestyle relay, Phelps swam the lead-off leg in 47.78, well off his 47.51 performance in Beijing, but the American team was able to edge out Russia and France for the gold.<ref>{{cite news |title=World Records Fall in Swimming, and It's Only Day 1 |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2009/07/27/sports/27swim.html |work=The New York Times |author=Karen Crouse |date=July 27, 2009 |access-date=August 5, 2009}}</ref> For his second race, the 200-meter freestyle, Phelps lost his first race in four years to Germany's [[Paul Biedermann]]. Phelps touched second in 1:43.22, but Biedermann smashed Phelps's record of 1:42.96 set in Beijing a year ago with a time of 1:42.00.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.omegatiming.com/File/Download?id=0001090B0022000000FFFFFFFFFFFF01 |title=2009 World Championships – 200 m freestyle results (final) |publisher=Omega Timing |access-date=August 10, 2016}}</ref> Phelps took the silver graciously, but coach [[Bob Bowman (coach)|Bob Bowman]] threatened to withdraw Phelps from international competition because Bowman claimed Biedermann had an unfair advantage because he was wearing a full [[polyurethane]] [[swimsuit]], specifically an [[Arena X-Glide]].<ref name="Distillations">{{cite journal|last1=Roberts|first1=Jacob |title=Winning Skin |journal=Distillations |date=2017|volume=2|issue=4|pages=8–15|url=https://www.sciencehistory.org/distillations/magazine/winning-skin|access-date=March 22, 2018}}</ref>
Bowman said, "It took me five years to get Michael from 1:46 to 1:42 and this guy has done it in 11 months. That's an amazing training performance. I'd like to know how to do that."<ref>{{cite news |title=Coach threatens to pull Phelps |url=http://sports.espn.go.com/oly/swimming/news/story?id=4360589 |publisher=ESPN |agency=Associated Press |date=July 28, 2009 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090731215829/http://sports.espn.go.com/oly/swimming/news/story?id=4360589 |archive-date=July 31, 2009 |access-date=September 4, 2010 |url-status=dead}}</ref> Phelps rebounded from this loss and for his third race, the 200-meter butterfly, Phelps won the gold and broke his own world record of 1:52.03 with a time of 1:51.51.<ref>{{cite news |title=Phelps bounces back from loss with record in 200-meter butterfly |url=http://sportsillustrated.cnn.com/2009/writers/brian_cazeneuve/07/29/phelps/ |work=Sports Illustrated |date=July 29, 2009 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100412041532/http://sportsillustrated.cnn.com/2009/writers/brian_cazeneuve/07/29/phelps/ |archive-date=April 12, 2010 |access-date=August 25, 2010 |url-status=dead  }}</ref> For his fourth race, the 4×200-meter freestyle relay, Phelps swam the lead-off leg in 1:44.49 as the team went on to win the gold medal and break the world record set the previous year.<ref>{{cite news |title=U.S. seals men's 4x200 relay title in record time |url=http://theusdaily.com/articles/viewarticle.jsp?id=811304&type=home |work=The US Daily |author=Matt Daily and Braden Reddall |date=July 31, 2009 |access-date=August 5, 2009 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110717040843/http://theusdaily.com/articles/viewarticle.jsp?id=811304&type=home |archive-date=July 17, 2011 |url-status=dead }}</ref> After his loss in the 200-meter freestyle, many thought Phelps was vulnerable coming into the final for the 100-meter butterfly.<ref>{{cite news |title=Phelps refrains from adding to the fire |url=http://tvnz.co.nz/othersports-news/phelps-refrains-adding-fire-2881392/ |publisher=Television New Zealand |agency=Reuters |date=July 31, 2009 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110614091622/http://tvnz.co.nz/othersports-news/phelps-refrains-adding-fire-2881392 |archive-date=June 14, 2011 |access-date=September 4, 2010 |url-status=dead  }}</ref> His closest competitor, [[Milorad Čavić]], who wore an Arena X-Glide (the same suit Biedermann beat Phelps with), thought people were making excuses for Phelps because he was wearing an [[LZR Racer]]. Čavić even offered to buy Phelps a new suit.<ref>{{cite news |title=Cavic: I'll buy Phelps new suit |url=http://sports.espn.go.com/oly/swimming/news/story?id=4368336 |publisher=ESPN |date=July 31, 2009 |access-date=June 22, 2010}}</ref> For his fifth race, the 100-meter butterfly, Phelps won the gold and became the first man to complete it in under 50 seconds, beating Čavić 49.82 to 49.95.<ref>{{cite news |title=Phelps goes under 50 seconds in 100m butterfly |url=https://www.irishtimes.com/newspaper/sport/2009/0803/1224251928081.html |work=The Irish Times |author=John Kenny |date=August 3, 2009 |access-date=August 5, 2009}}</ref> The victory prompted a fierce celebration from Phelps.<ref>{{cite news |title=Phelps savours triumph over rival Cavic |url=http://news.smh.com.au/breaking-news-sport/phelps-savours-triumph-over-rival-cavic-20090802-e5eb.html |work=The Sydney Morning Herald |author=Rebecca Bryan |date=August 2, 2009 |access-date=June 22, 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120606133326/http://news.smh.com.au/breaking-news-sport/phelps-savours-triumph-over-rival-cavic-20090802-e5eb.html |archive-date=June 6, 2012 |url-status=dead  }}</ref> For his final event, the 4×100-meter medley relay, Phelps won his fifth gold medal. Phelps, along with teammates [[Aaron Peirsol]], [[Eric Shanteau]], and [[David Walters (swimmer)|David Walters]], set a new world record in the event with a time of 3 minutes, 27.28 seconds.<ref>{{cite news |title=Phelps Leaves Rome With Another Gold |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2009/08/03/sports/03swim.html |work=The New York Times |author=Karen Crouse |date=August 2, 2009 |access-date=August 5, 2009}}</ref>

===2010 Pan Pacific championships===
{{MedalTableTop|name=no|header=[[2010 Pan Pacific Swimming Championships|2010 Pan Pacific Championships]]}}
{{MedalGold | [[2010 Pan Pacific Swimming Championships – Men's 100 metre butterfly|100 m butterfly]] | 50.86}}
{{MedalGold | [[2010 Pan Pacific Swimming Championships – Men's 200 metre butterfly|200 m butterfly]] | 1:54.11}}
{{MedalGold | [[2010 Pan Pacific Swimming Championships – Men's 4 × 100 metre freestyle relay|4×100 m freestyle]] | 3:11.74}}
{{MedalGold | [[2010 Pan Pacific Swimming Championships – Men's 4 × 200 metre freestyle relay|4×200 m freestyle]] | 7:03.84}}
{{MedalGold | [[2010 Pan Pacific Swimming Championships – Men's 4 × 100 metre medley relay|4×100 m medley]] | 3:32.48}}
{{MedalBottom}}

At the [[2010 USA Swimming Championships|2010 National Championships]], Phelps competed in five individual events. In the 200-meter freestyle, Phelps won ahead of [[Ryan Lochte]] in a time of 1:45.61.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.omegatiming.com/File/Download?id=00010A110016000000FFFFFFFFFFFF01 |title=2010 ConocoPhillips National Championships – 200 m freestyle results (final) |publisher=Omega Timing |access-date=August 10, 2016}}</ref> About an hour later, Phelps returned to the pool to win the 200-meter butterfly.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.omegatiming.com/File/Download?id=00010A110019000000FFFFFFFFFFFF01 |title=2010 ConocoPhillips National Championships – 200 m butterfly results (final) |publisher=Omega Timing |access-date=August 10, 2016}}</ref> But Phelps was not happy with his performance and called it the "worst" 200-meter butterfly of his life. In the 100-meter butterfly, Phelps won his 50th national title in 50.65.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.omegatiming.com/File/Download?id=00010A110022000000FFFFFFFFFFFF01 |title=2010 ConocoPhillips National Championships – 100 m butterfly results (final) |publisher=Omega Timing |access-date=August 10, 2016}}</ref> After the race, Phelps said he was "fairly pleased" with the result.<ref>{{cite news |title=No surprises -Phelps takes gold |url=http://www.sfgate.com/cgi-bin/article.cgi?f=/c/a/2010/08/05/SPMT1EPK99.DTL |newspaper=San Francisco Chronicle |agency=Associated Press |date=August 6, 2010 |archive-url=https://archive.today/20120917220052/http://www.sfgate.com/cgi-bin/article.cgi?f=/c/a/2010/08/05/SPMT1EPK99.DTL |archive-date=September 17, 2012 |access-date=September 4, 2010 |url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Michael Phelps 'fairly pleased' after making history at US nationals |url=https://www.theguardian.com/sport/2010/aug/06/michael-phelps-us-nationals-100m-butterfly |work=The Guardian |date=August 6, 2008 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100816035928/http://www.guardian.co.uk/sport/2010/aug/06/michael-phelps-us-nationals-100m-butterfly |archive-date=August 16, 2010 |access-date=September 4, 2010 |location=London |url-status=dead  }}</ref> In the 200-meter individual medley, Phelps finished second to Lochte 1:55.94 to 1:54.84.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.omegatiming.com/File/Download?id=00010A11002F000000FFFFFFFFFFFF01 |title=2010 ConocoPhillips National Championships – 200 m individual medley results (final) |publisher=Omega Timing |access-date=August 10, 2016}}</ref> It was the first time Lochte had beat Phelps in a major national meet.<ref>{{cite news |title=Ryan Lochte upsets Michael Phelps at national swimming championships |url=https://articles.latimes.com/2010/aug/06/sports/la-sp-national-swimming-20100807 |work=Los Angeles Times |date=August 6, 2010 |access-date=August 9, 2010 |first=Lisa |last=Dillman}}</ref> In the 200-meter backstroke, Phelps finished in 4th place in 1:56.98.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.omegatiming.com/File/Download?id=00010A11003A000000FFFFFFFFFFFF01 |title=2010 ConocoPhillips National Championships – 200 m backstroke results (final) |publisher=Omega Timing |access-date=August 10, 2016}}</ref>

On the first day of competition at the [[2010 Pan Pacific Swimming Championships]], Phelps opted out swimming in the final of the 200-meter freestyle to focus on the 200-meter butterfly. In the 200-meter butterfly, Phelps led from start to finish, coming in first with a time of 1:54.11. Although it was much slower than his 1:51.51 time from the previous year, Phelps had not lost a 200-meter butterfly final since 2002.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.omegatiming.com/File/Download?id=00010A0B0011000000FFFFFFFFFFFF01 |title=2010 Pan Pacific Swimming Championships – 200 m butterfly results (final) |publisher=Omega Timing |access-date=August 10, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Phelps extends dominance in 200 fly at Pan Pacs |url=https://www.google.com/hostednews/ap/article/ALeqM5gRdGMzTqPfw-5pdKxhGzXd7YkW_gD9HMAF1G0 |agency=Associated Press |date=August 18, 2010 |archive-url=https://www.webcitation.org/5s5gsNxKs?url=http://www.google.com/hostednews/ap/article/ALeqM5gRdGMzTqPfw-5pdKxhGzXd7YkW_gD9HMAF1G0 |archive-date=August 19, 2010 |access-date=August 18, 2010 |url-status=dead  }}</ref> On day two of the competition, Phelps swam in the heats of the 400-meter individual medley and contributed in the 4×200-meter freestyle relay. In the heats of the 400-meter individual medley, Phelps failed to make the A final, with Lochte and [[Tyler Clary]] taking the top two American positions.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://omegatiming.com/File/Download?id=00010A0B0019000000FFFFFFFFFFFF01 |title=2010 Pan Pacific Swimming Championships – 400 m individual medley results (heats) |publisher=Omega Timing |access-date=August 2, 2016}}</ref> Phelps did not swim in the B final of the 400-meter individual medley. In the 4×200-meter freestyle relay, Phelps, with [[Peter Vanderkaay]], [[Ricky Berens]], and Lochte, finished first ahead of Japan and Australia.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://omegatiming.com/File/Download?id=00010A0B0027000000FFFFFFFFFFFF01 |title=2010 Pan Pacific Swimming Championships – 4×200&nbsp;m freestyle relay results (final) |publisher=Omega Timing |access-date=August 2, 2016}}</ref> On day three of the competition, Phelps competed in the 100-meter butterfly and contributed in the 4×100-meter freestyle relay. In the 100-meter butterfly, Phelps finished first in a time of 50.86, a championship record.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://omegatiming.com/File/Download?id=00010A0B0033000000FFFFFFFFFFFF01 |title=2010 Pan Pacific Swimming Championships – 100 m butterfly results (final) |publisher=Omega Timing |access-date=August 2, 2016}}</ref> In the 4×100-meter freestyle relay, Phelps, with Lochte, [[Jason Lezak]], and [[Nathan Adrian]], finished first ahead of Australia and South Africa. As the lead-off leg in the 4×100-meter freestyle relay, Phelps set the [[List of Pan Pacific Championships records in swimming|championship record]] in the 100-meter freestyle with a time of 48.13.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://omegatiming.com/File/Download?id=00010A0B0039000000FFFFFFFFFFFF01 |title=2010 Pan Pacific Swimming Championships – 4×100&nbsp;m freestyle relay results (final) |publisher=Omega Timing |access-date=August 2, 2016}}</ref> In his final event, Phelps swam in the 4×100-meter medley relay with [[Aaron Peirsol]], [[Mark Gangloff]], and Adrian and finished first ahead of Japan and Australia.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://omegatiming.com/File/Download?id=00010A0B004B000000FFFFFFFFFFFF01 |title=2010 Pan Pacific Swimming Championships – 4×100&nbsp;m medley relay results (final) |publisher=Omega Timing |access-date=August 2, 2016}}</ref>

===2011 World championships===
{{MedalTableTop|name=no|header=[[Swimming at the 2011 World Aquatics Championships|2011 World Championships]]}}
{{MedalGold | [[Swimming at the 2011 World Aquatics Championships – Men's 100 metre butterfly|100 m butterfly]] | 50.71}}
{{MedalGold | [[Swimming at the 2011 World Aquatics Championships – Men's 200 metre butterfly|200 m butterfly]] | 1:53.34}}
{{MedalGold | [[Swimming at the 2011 World Aquatics Championships – Men's 4 × 200 metre freestyle relay|4×200 m freestyle]] | 7:02.67}}
{{MedalGold | [[Swimming at the 2011 World Aquatics Championships – Men's 4 × 100 metre medley relay|4×100 m medley]] | 3:32.06}}
{{MedalSilver | [[Swimming at the 2011 World Aquatics Championships – Men's 200 metre freestyle|200 m freestyle]] | 1:44.79}}
{{MedalSilver | [[Swimming at the 2011 World Aquatics Championships – Men's 200 metre individual medley|200 m medley]] | 1:54.16}}
{{MedalBronze | [[Swimming at the 2011 World Aquatics Championships – Men's 4 × 100 metre freestyle relay|4×100 m freestyle]] | 3:11.96}}
{{MedalBottom}}

In his first event at the 2011 World Aquatics Championships in Shanghai, Phelps won bronze in the 4×100-meter freestyle relay with [[Garrett Weber-Gale]], Jason Lezak, and [[Nathan Adrian]].<ref>{{cite news|title=FINA World Championships, Swimming: Australia Stuns France, U.S. For Men's 400 Free Relay Triumph; Two New Textile Bests |url=http://www.swimmingworldmagazine.com/lane9/news/27647.asp?q=FINA-World-Championships,-Swimming:--Australia-Stuns-France,-U.S.-For-Men's-400-Free-Relay-Triumph;-Two-New-Textile-Bests |work=Swimming World |date=July 24, 2011 |access-date=July 27, 2011 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121114045304/http://www.swimmingworldmagazine.com/lane9/news/27647.asp?q=FINA-World-Championships%2C-Swimming%3A--Australia-Stuns-France%2C-U.S.-For-Men%27s-400-Free-Relay-Triumph%3B-Two-New-Textile-Bests |archive-date=November 14, 2012}}</ref> This was Phelps's first bronze in a [[FINA World Aquatics Championships|World Aquatics Championships]]. Phelps swam the lead-off leg in 48.08, the second-best lead-off in the field behind [[James Magnussen]]'s 47.49. In his second event, the 200-meter freestyle, Phelps won silver for the second consecutive time at a World Aquatics Championships. This time he finished second to [[Ryan Lochte]] in the event with a time of 1:44.79, compared to Lochte's time of 1:44.44.<ref>{{cite news |title=FINA World Championships, Swimming: Ryan Lochte Bests Michael Phelps For 200 Free Gold |url=https://www.swimmingworldmagazine.com/news/fina-world-championships-swimming-ryan-lochte-bests-michael-phelps-for-200-free-gold/ |work=Swimming World |date=July 26, 2011 |access-date=November 15, 2016}}</ref> In his third final, the 200-meter butterfly, he won his first gold medal with a time of 1:53.34 to become the first swimmer to win five gold medals in one discipline at the World Aquatics Championships.<ref>{{cite news |title=FINA World Championships, Swimming: Michael Phelps Closes Out Takeshi Matsuda for Gold Medal |url=https://www.swimmingworldmagazine.com/news/fina-world-championships-swimming-michael-phelps-closes-out-takeshi-matsuda-for-gold-medal/ |work=Swimming World |date=July 27, 2011 |access-date=November 15, 2016}}</ref> In his fourth event, the 200-meter individual medley, Phelps again finished second to Lochte in a personal best of 1:54.16, which was 0.16 behind Lochte who swam a new world record.<ref>{{cite news |title=FINA World Championships, Swimming: Ryan Lochte Sets First Post Techsuit-Era World Record |url=https://www.swimmingworldmagazine.com/news/flash-fina-world-championships-swimming-ryan-lochte-sets-first-long-course-post-techsuit-era-world-record-video-included/ |work=Swimming World |date=July 28, 2011 |access-date=November 15, 2016}}</ref> It was Phelps's 30th medal in the World Aquatics Championships. Shortly after completing the semi-finals of the 100-meter butterfly, Phelps competed in the 4×200-meter freestyle relay with [[Peter Vanderkaay]], [[Ricky Berens]], and [[Ryan Lochte]]. Phelps's team won the gold medal in a time of 7:02.67. Phelps swam the lead-off leg in 1:45.53, the third-best leg in the field.<ref>{{cite news|title=FINA World Championships, Swimming: Ryan Lochte's Monster Anchor Leg Secures United States Victory in 800 Free Relay |url=http://www.swimmingworldmagazine.com/lane9/news/27740.asp?q=FINA-World-Championships,-Swimming:-Ryan-Lochte's-Monster-Anchor-Leg-Secures-United-States-Victory-in-800-Free-Relay |work=Swimming World |date=July 29, 2011 |access-date=July 29, 2011 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121114045257/http://www.swimmingworldmagazine.com/lane9/news/27740.asp?q=FINA-World-Championships%2C-Swimming%3A-Ryan-Lochte%27s-Monster-Anchor-Leg-Secures-United-States-Victory-in-800-Free-Relay |archive-date=November 14, 2012}}</ref> In the 100-meter butterfly, Phelps won his third consecutive title (also winning in 2007 and 2009) and second individual title of the meet with a time of 50.71.<ref>{{cite news |title=FINA World Championships, Swimming: Michael Phelps Threepeats 100 Fly |url=https://www.swimmingworldmagazine.com/news/fina-world-championships-swimming-michael-phelps-threepeats-100-fly/ |work=Swimming World |date=July 30, 2011 |access-date=November 15, 2016}}</ref> In his last event, the 4×100-meter medley relay, Phelps teamed with [[Nick Thoman]], [[Mark Gangloff]], and [[Nathan Adrian]] to win gold in a time of 3:32.06. Phelps's butterfly leg of 50.57 was by far the fastest butterfly leg in the field.<ref>{{cite news |title=FINA World Championships, Swimming: United States Edges Australia for 400 Medley Relay Win |url=http://www.swimmingworldmagazine.com/news/fina-world-championships-swimming-united-states-edges-australia-for-400-medley-relay-win/ |work=Swimming World |date=July 31, 2011 |access-date=November 15, 2016}}</ref>

