{{MedalBottom}}

====Trials====
For the [[2012 Summer Olympics]] in London, Phelps originally stated he would never do eight events again, and would instead try new events. Phelps said, "I keep saying I want to go down and start sprinting, but Bob [Bowman, Phelps's coach] really isn't so keen on that ... I don't think that's going to happen ... Over the next four years, I'd like to try some different events, maybe not do some of the events I did here."<ref>Schaller, p.228.</ref><ref>Schaller, p. 229.</ref> However, at the [[2012 United States Olympic Trials (swimming)|2012 United States Olympic Trials]], the qualifying meet for the 2012 Summer Olympics, Phelps qualified in the same eight events that he swam in Beijing in 2008. He later dropped the 200-meter freestyle from his program, as he stated he wanted to focus on the 4×100-meter freestyle relay.<ref name="sports.yahoo.com">{{cite web |author=Paul Newberry |url=https://www.yahoo.com/news/phelps-locks-another-8-race-program-london-003227591--oly.html |title=Phelps locks up another 8-race program in London – Yahoo! Sports |publisher=Yahoo! |date=July 2, 2012 |access-date=November 15, 2016}}</ref> During the trials, Phelps finished first in the 200-meter freestyle, 100-meter butterfly, 200-meter butterfly, 200-meter individual medley, and second in the 400-meter individual medley. In making his fourth Olympic team, Phelps holds the record for men for the most Olympic appearances in swimming representing the United States.<ref>{{cite web |last=Powers |first=John |title=Michael Phelps earns expected Olympic berth |url=https://www.bostonglobe.com/sports/2012/06/26/phelps-dives-right-earns-expected-berth/AcDM1AfTkPeBy5tcGUeHiL/story.html |work=Boston Globe |access-date=June 26, 2012}}</ref>

====London====
[[File:London 2012 100m butterfly heats.jpg|thumb|upright=1.25|right|In his [[Swimming at the 2012 Summer Olympics – Men's 100 metre butterfly|100m butterfly heat]], Phelps (fourth from top) was 8th at the 50m split before winning his heat and qualifying for the semi-finals]]
On July 28, 2012, Phelps placed eighth in the morning prelims for the 400-meter individual medley. Phelps, the two-time defending Olympic champion, won his heat in 4 minutes, 13.33 seconds with a time that was well off his world record of 4:03.84 set four years earlier in Beijing, when Phelps won a record eight gold medals. He out-touched [[László Cseh]] by 0.07 seconds in his [[Swimming at the 2012 Summer Olympics – Men's 400 metre individual medley#Heats|heat]] to qualify last for the final, locking out Cseh. In his first finals of the Summer Olympics, Phelps placed fourth behind fellow American [[Ryan Lochte]], [[Thiago Pereira]] of Brazil, and [[Kosuke Hagino]] of Japan in the [[Swimming at the 2012 Summer Olympics – Men's 400 metre individual medley|400-meter individual medley]]. It was the first time Phelps failed to medal in an Olympic event since 2000.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/olympics/18910454 |title=Ryan Lochte wins medley gold as Michael Phelps finishes fourth |date=July 29, 2012 |access-date=July 7, 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121108034421/http://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/olympics/18910454 |archive-date=November 8, 2012 |url-status=dead  }}</ref> The next night, in his second event of the Games, he got a silver as a member of the [[Swimming at the 2012 Summer Olympics – Men's 4 × 100 metre freestyle relay|4×100-meter free relay]]. Phelps swam the fastest leg of the US relay team and the second-fastest of anyone in the race.<ref>{{cite news |last=Layden |first=Tim |title=Phelps, U.S. fail to recreate Beijing magic, drop to silver in 400 relay |url=http://sportsillustrated.cnn.com/2012/olympics/2012/writers/tim_layden/07/29/france-us-400-relay-olympics/index.html |date=July 29, 2012 |work=Sports Illustrated |access-date=July 29, 2012}}</ref>

On July 31, 2012, Phelps won a silver medal in the [[Swimming at the 2012 Summer Olympics – Men's 200 metre butterfly|200-meter butterfly]] behind South African [[Chad le Clos]] by 5/100ths of a second, and a gold medal in the [[Swimming at the 2012 Summer Olympics – Men's 4 × 200 metre freestyle relay|4×200-meter freestyle relay]], thereby equaling and then surpassing [[Larisa Latynina]] to become the [[List of multiple Olympic medalists|all-time record holder]] for most Olympic medals won.<ref>{{cite news |title='Fab Five' brings home gymnastics gold |url=http://edition.cnn.com/2012/07/31/sport/olympics-day-wrap/index.html?hpt=hp_c1 |work=CNN|access-date=August 1, 2012 |date=August 1, 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Michael Phelps breaks record by reaching 19 Olympic medals in London |url=https://www.theguardian.com/sport/2012/aug/01/michael-phelps-19-olympic-medals-london?newsfeed=true |work=The Guardian |access-date=August 1, 2012 |first=Owen |last=Gibson |date=August 1, 2012}}</ref> Latynina was present at the race and asked to be the presenter of Phelps's medal, but was told that Olympic rules would not allow it. She called Phelps deserving of the record.<ref>{{cite news |last=Longman |first=Jeré |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2012/08/01/sports/olympics/gymnast-larisa-latynina-is-elegant-reminder-of-olympics-history.html?pagewanted=1&_r=2 |title=Phelps Tops Another Olympian, but at 77, She Grins |date=July 31, 2012 |page=A1 |access-date=August 1, 2012 |work=The New York Times}}</ref>

On August 2, 2012, Phelps won his 16th Olympic gold medal when he edged out Ryan Lochte to win the [[Swimming at the 2012 Summer Olympics - Men's 200 metre individual medley|200-meter individual medley]] with a time of 1:54.27, and by that victory also became the first male swimmer to win the same event in three consecutive Olympics.<ref>{{ cite web | title = Michael Phelps wins 16th career gold | url = http://espn.go.com/olympics/summer/2012/swimming/story/_/id/8227208/2012-summer-olympics-michael-phelps-outduels-ryan-lochte-take-gold-200-im-20th-medal | publisher = ESPN | date = August 3, 2012 | access-date = August 3, 2012}}</ref> [[Rebecca Soni]] and Phelps (twice) are the only swimmers to successfully defend an individual title from the 2008 Games.<ref>{{cite news |last=Crouse |first=Karen |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2012/08/03/sports/olympics/soni-first-repeat-winner-in-swimming-franklin.html |title=Soni Sets World Record to Win 200 Breaststroke |date=August 2, 2012 |page=A1 |access-date=August 4, 2012 |work=The New York Times}}</ref> This win also marked Phelps's fifth Olympic title in the individual medley, breaking the record of four shared by Hungarian [[Tamás Darnyi]] and Ukrainian [[Yana Klochkova]].

He repeated the achievement of winning the same event at three Olympics the following evening, winning the Olympic gold medal in the [[Swimming at the 2012 Summer Olympics – Men's 100 metre butterfly|100 m butterfly]], his last individual event.<ref>{{cite news |last=Zaccardi |first=Nick |title=Phelps surges toward exit as Franklin, Ledeckey rise to stardom |url=http://sportsillustrated.cnn.com/2012/olympics/2012/writers/nick_zaccardi/08/03/michael-phelps-olympics-swimming/index.html?eref=sihp&sct=hp_t11_a0 |work=London 2012 |publisher=cnnsi.com |date=August 3, 2012 |access-date=August 3, 2012}}</ref> After two very close victories in the 100 m butterfly at the 2004 and 2008 Olympics (by 0.04 and 0.01 sec, respectively), in this race Phelps beat Le Clos and [[Yevgeny Korotyshkin]], who tied for silver, by 0.23 sec.

Phelps's final event was the [[Swimming at the 2012 Summer Olympics – Men's 4 × 100 metre medley relay|4×100-meter medley relay]] in which he went on to win his 18th career gold medal and his 22nd overall. By winning 4 gold and 2 silver medals, Phelps concluded the 2012 Olympics as the most successful swimmer of the meet for the third Olympics in a row.<ref>{{cite news |title=2012 London Olympics: Michael Phelps Leads All Swimmers With Six Medals |url=http://www.swimmingworldmagazine.com/lane9/news/World/31591.asp?q=2012-London-Olympics:-Michael-Phelps-Leads-All-Swimmers-With-Six-Medals |archive-url=https://archive.today/20130203075830/http://www.swimmingworldmagazine.com/lane9/news/World/31591.asp?q=2012-London-Olympics:-Michael-Phelps-Leads-All-Swimmers-With-Six-Medals |url-status=dead |archive-date=February 3, 2013 |access-date=August 4, 2012 |newspaper=Swimming World |date=August 5, 2012}}</ref><ref name=number1>{{cite news |last=Almond |first=Elliott |title=Olympics: Michael Phelps shows once more why he's the gold standard in swimming |url=http://www.mercurynews.com/ci_21231419/olympics-michael-phelps-shows-once-more-why-hes?source=most_viewed |access-date=August 4, 2012 |newspaper=Mercury News |date=August 3, 2012}}</ref>
After his last event, the international swimming federation [[FINA]] honored Phelps with an award commemorating his standing as the most decorated Olympian ever.<ref>{{cite news |title=Phelps ends career with gold in medley relay |url=http://sportsillustrated.cnn.com/2012/olympics/2012/08/04/phelps-medley-relay-gold.ap/index.html |access-date=August 4, 2012 |newspaper=Sports Illustrated |date=August 4, 2012}}</ref>

===First retirement===
After the 2012 Olympics, Phelps retired from swimming, stating: "I'm done. I'm finished. I'm retired. I'm done. No more," and that "I just wanted to be done with swimming and didn't want anything to do with the sport anymore."<ref>{{cite news |last1=Bruner |first1=Raisa |title=All the Times Michael Phelps Has Totally Insisted He's Going to Retire |url=http://time.com/4452285/rio-2016-olympics-michael-phelps-retirement/ |access-date=August 17, 2016 |agency=Time |date=August 15, 2016}}</ref>

===2014 comeback from retirement===
{{MedalTableTop|name=no|header=[[2014 Pan Pacific Swimming Championships|2014 Pan Pacific Championships]]}}
{{MedalGold | [[2014 Pan Pacific Swimming Championships – Men's 100 metre butterfly|100 m butterfly]] | 51.29}}
{{MedalGold | [[2014 Pan Pacific Swimming Championships – Men's 4 × 200 metre freestyle relay|4×200 m freestyle]] | 7:05.17}}
{{MedalGold | [[2014 Pan Pacific Swimming Championships – Men's 4 × 100 metre medley relay|4×100 m medley]] | 3:29.94 (CR)}}
{{MedalSilver | [[2014 Pan Pacific Swimming Championships – Men's 200 metre individual medley|200 m medley]] | 1:56.04}}
{{MedalSilver | [[2014 Pan Pacific Swimming Championships – Men's 4 × 100 metre freestyle relay|4×100 m freestyle]] | 3:13.36}}
{{MedalBottom}}
In April 2014, Phelps announced he would come out of retirement, and would enter an event later that month.<ref>{{citation |url=http://6abc.com/archive/9503243/ |title=Olympic Great Michael Phelps Ending Retirement |access-date=April 14, 2014 |last=Harris |first=Beth |date=April 14, 2014 |publisher=[[ABC News]]}}</ref> In May 2014, he won the 100-meter butterfly event at the Arena Grand Prix in Charlotte, North Carolina.<ref>{{cite news |last=Goldberg |first=Rob |date=May 16, 2014 |title=Michael Phelps at Charlotte Grand Prix 2014: Race Results and Twitter Reaction |url=http://bleacherreport.com/articles/2066104-michael-phelps-at-charlotte-grand-prix-2014-race-results-and-twitter-reaction |newspaper=[[Bleacher Report]] |access-date=June 9, 2014}}</ref> Phelps was reportedly motivated by the national team's failure to win the men's 4 × 100 m freestyle relay since their [[Swimming at the 2008 Summer Olympics – Men's 4 × 100 metre freestyle relay|Beijing 2008]] and [[2009 World Aquatics Championships|Rome 2009]] titles.<ref>Forde, Pat. [https://sports.yahoo.com/news/the-story-of-how-michael-phelps-and-the-best-turn-ever-done-made-olympic-magic-065358629.html "The story of how Michael Phelps and 'the best turn ever done' made Olympic magic"], yahoosports.com. August 8, 2016.</ref><ref name="nbcolympics.com1">{{Cite web|url=http://www.nbcolympics.com/news/posnanski-2016-likely-be-michael-phelps-favorite-olympic-games|title=Posnanski: 2016 likely to be Michael Phelps' favorite Olympic Games}}</ref> The relationship between Phelps and coach Bob Bowman had deteriorated in the preparations for London 2012, so Phelps convinced a skeptical Bowman that he "wasn't training for history. He wasn't training for the medals. He wasn't even training for all the fans. This time Phelps wanted to swim for himself...and enjoy the journey".<ref name="nbcolympics.com1"/> Since his returning from retirement in 2014, Phelps "scaled back his calorie intake" and "increased his postswim ice baths". By the 2016 Olympic Trials, despite his age Phelps "felt physically stronger in the water, perhaps because of drills Bowman added to his pool workouts, like multiple repeats of 40 seconds of dolphin kicking while hugging a 10-pound weight to his chest".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2016/06/26/sports/olympics/michael-phelps-swimming-rehab.html|title=Seeking Answers, Michael Phelps Finds Himself|first=Karen|last=Crouse|date=June 24, 2016|via=NYTimes.com}}</ref>

===2015 US Nationals===
After having been dropped from the team for the [[2015 World Aquatics Championships]] for a [[DUI]], Phelps instead competed in the [[United States Swimming National Championships|US National Championships]] (long course) in San Antonio as his target meet of the summer. He won gold medals in the 100-meter butterfly (50.45 s),<ref>{{cite news |title=Men's 100-meter butterfly Final |url=http://www.omegatiming.com/File/Download?id=00010F020B00030D02FFFFFFFFFFFF02 |newspaper=Omega Timing |date=August 8, 2015}}</ref> 200-meter butterfly (1:52.94),<ref>{{cite news |title=Men's 200-meter butterfly Final |url=http://www.omegatiming.com/File/Download?id=00010F020B00030E02FFFFFFFFFFFF02 |newspaper=Omega Timing |date=August 7, 2015}}</ref> and the 200-meter individual medley (1:54.75).<ref>{{cite news |title=Men's 200-meter Individual Medley Final |url=http://www.omegatiming.com/File/Download?id=00010F020B00041002FFFFFFFFFFFF02 |newspaper=Omega Timing |date=August 9, 2015}}</ref> In each of these events he swam the fastest time in the world for 2015.

In December 2015 at the Winter Nationals in [[Federal Way, Washington|Federal Way]], Phelps won titles in the same three events, again in long course, bringing his career total to 62 national titles.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.swimvortex.com/with-156-11-outing-in-200-fly-michael-phelps-grabs-third-title-of-winter-nationals/ |title=With 1:56.11 Outing in 200 Fly, Michael Phelps Grabs Third Title of Winter Nationals |first1=John |last1=Lohn |date=December 6, 2015 |publisher=Swimvortex |access-date=December 6, 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151212081041/http://www.swimvortex.com/with-156-11-outing-in-200-fly-michael-phelps-grabs-third-title-of-winter-nationals/ |archive-date=December 12, 2015 |url-status=dead  }}</ref>

