{{MedalBottom}}

====Trials====
At the [[2016 United States Olympic Trials (swimming)|US trials]] in Omaha for the [[2016 Summer Olympics]], Phelps won the 200 m butterfly (1:54.84), the 200 m individual medley (1:55.91), and the 100 m butterfly (51.00 s) events. This made him the first American male swimmer, and the second American swimmer overall after [[Dara Torres]], to qualify for a fifth Olympics.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://swimswam.com/phelps-makes-fifth-olympic-team/ |title=Michael Phelps makes fifth Olympic Team |first1=Hannah |last1=Hecht |date=June 29, 2016 |publisher=Swimswam |access-date=June 30, 2016}}</ref> Phelps's 100 m freestyle times at the Trials were not impressive. However at a final training camp in Atlanta a week before heading to Rio, Phelps put out "the fourth-fastest flat-start time of the year" in a 100 free time trial, automatically securing one of the seven spots on the Men's 4 × 100 metre freestyle relay for the Olympics.<ref name="thestar.com">{{cite web|url=https://www.thestar.com/sports/olympics/2016/08/08/can-extraterrestrial-michael-phelps-bag-6-rio-olympics-gold-medals.html|title=Can 'extraterrestrial' Michael Phelps bag 6 Rio Olympics gold medals?|first=Paul|last=Newberry|date=August 8, 2016|via=Toronto Star}}</ref>

====Rio de Janeiro====
Phelps was chosen to be the [[United States at the 2016 Summer Olympics|American]] [[List of flag bearers for the United States at the Olympics|flag bearer]] at the [[Olympic Games ceremony#Opening|opening ceremony]], which was the first Olympic opening ceremony that he would attend.<ref name="auto1">{{Cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2016/07/20/sports/michael-phelps-is-named-a-captain-on-the-us-mens-olympic-swim-team.html |title=Michael Phelps Is Named a Captain on the U.S. Men's Olympic Swim Team |date=July 19, 2016 |newspaper=The New York Times |issn=0362-4331 |access-date=August 15, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://edition.cnn.com/2016/08/03/sport/michael-phelps-rio-olympics-team-usa-flag-bearer/index.html |title=Michael Phelps selected as U.S. flag bearer for Rio Olympics |first1=Jill |last1=Martin |date=August 3, 2016 |publisher=[[CNN]] |access-date=August 3, 2016}}</ref> Phelps was also voted by the U.S. Olympic swim team as one of six [[Captain (sports)|team captains]] for the [[United States at the 2016 Summer Olympics|US delegation]] to the Olympics.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.people.com/article/veterans-helm-us-olympic-swim-team-michael-phelps-captain |title=Michael Phelps Will Captain for First Time as Veterans Helm U.S. Olympic Swim Teams |access-date=August 15, 2016}}</ref> He displayed a relaxed sociable demeanor in the athletes' village and in press conferences; this pleasant behavior was in stark contrast to his isolation in previous Olympics.<ref name="nbcolympics.com1"/> He was accompanied by fiancée Nicole Johnson and son Boomer.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.cbc.ca/sports/olympics/summer/aquatics/whats-next-michael-phelps-1.3731722 |title=The father, the millionaire, the reformed: Michael Phelps ponders future |first1=Callum |last1=Ng |date=August 23, 2016 |publisher=[[Canadian Broadcasting Corporation]] |access-date=August 24, 2016}}</ref>

In his first event on August 7, the [[Swimming at the 2016 Summer Olympics – Men's 4 × 100 metre freestyle relay|4 × 100 m freestyle relay]], he won his first gold medal of the 2016 Games and his 19th Olympic gold medal overall. Phelps swam the second leg with what his coach Bob Bowman described as "maybe the best turn that's ever been done",<ref>Laydon, Tim, [https://www.si.com/olympics/2016/08/08/michael-phelps-rio-us-4x100-free-relay-gold-medal "Reborn Michael Phelps plays pivotal role in U.S. 4x100 free relay gold"], [[Sports Illustrated]], August 8, 2016.</ref> overtaking France's [[Fabien Gilot]] to give his American teammates a lead which they would not relinquish.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://sports.yahoo.com/news/the-story-of-how-michael-phelps-and-the-best-turn-ever-done-made-olympic-magic-065358629.html|title=The story of how Michael Phelps and 'the best turn ever done' made Olympic magic|website=Yahoo Sports}}</ref> Phelps's leg proved to be the decisive factor in the race, and Gilot later remarked "As fast as my teammates were, the extraterrestrial that is Phelps was faster".<ref name="thestar.com"/> Phelps achieved a split time of 47.12, the fourth-fastest of the field (the three fastest times were posted by the team anchors),<ref name="thestar.com"/> which was also faster than any of his relay splits at the last three Olympics.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ctvnews.ca/sports/i-m-very-pleased-for-michael-phelps-6-golds-within-reach-in-rio-1.3019293|title='I'm very pleased': For Michael Phelps, 6 golds within reach in Rio|first=Paul|last=Newberry|date=August 8, 2016|website=CTVNews}}</ref><ref name="nbcolympics.com">{{Cite web|url=http://www.nbcolympics.com/news/abrahamson-americans-recaptured-magic-freestyle-relay-triumph|title=Abrahamson: Americans recaptured the magic with freestyle relay triumph}}</ref>
[[File:Phelps carries Stars & Stripes (28726351981).jpg|thumb|300px|right|Phelps [[List of flag bearers for the United States at the Olympics|carrying the flag]] on behalf of athletes from the United States  during the [[2016 Summer Olympics Parade of Nations|parade of nation]] within the [[2016 Summer Olympics opening ceremony]]]]

In his second event on August 9, the [[Swimming at the 2016 Summer Olympics – Men's 200 metre butterfly|200-meter butterfly]], he became the first swimmer in history to make five finals in the same event, after finishing 5th in 2000, 1st in 2004 and 2008, and 2nd in 2012.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://swimswam.com/phelps-becomes-first-reach-five-consecutive-finals/ |title=Phelps becomes the first to reach five consecutive finals |first1=Jeff |last1=Grace |date=August 9, 2016 |publisher=Swimswam |access-date=August 9, 2016}}</ref> At Rio, he won the title that he had lost to [[Chad le Clos]] four years earlier in London, edging [[Masato Sakai (swimmer)|Masato Sakai]] by 0.04 s. Phelps stated that winning back this title had been the main goal during his comeback.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.swimvortex.com/michael-phelps-i-really-wanted-that-one-back-mission-repossession-accomplished/ |title=Michael Phelps: 'I really wanted that one back' – mission repossession accomplished |first1=Craig |last1=Lord |date=August 9, 2016 |publisher=Swimvortex |access-date=August 10, 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160811134753/http://www.swimvortex.com/michael-phelps-i-really-wanted-that-one-back-mission-repossession-accomplished/ |archive-date=August 11, 2016 |url-status=dead  }}</ref> The preliminary and final of that event was heavily hyped as a rematch between Phelps and Le Clos. The relationship between Le Clos and Phelps had been cordial back in 2012–13 but it deteriorated in 2014 when Phelps came back from retirement and suggested that the current butterfly times were slow.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.sbnation.com/2016/8/9/12410916/2016-summer-olympics-michael-phelps-chad-le-clos-swimming-rivarly-stare|title=The history behind Michael Phelps' death stare|first=Christian|last=D'Andrea|date=August 9, 2016|website=[[SB Nation]]}}</ref> In the ready room prior to the preliminary race, Le Clos's shadow boxing while Phelps "glowered in a corner" spawned the Internet meme with the hashtag #PhelpsFace. Le Clos's Wikipedia biography was even vandalized after the event final.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://time.com/4446837/rio-2016-olympics-michael-phelps-chad-le-clos/|title=The Internet Went Wild For Michael Phelps' Win Over Chad le Clos|website=Time}}</ref> At age 31, the victory made Phelps not only the oldest male champion,<ref name="auto">{{Cite web |url=https://www.sbnation.com/2016/8/9/12419516/michael-phelps-gold-medal-record-leonidas-of-rhodes |title=Michael Phelps broke a 2,168-year-old Olympic record |last=Sherman |first=Rodger |date=August 12, 2016 |publisher=[[SB Nation]] |access-date=August 12, 2016}}</ref> but also the oldest individual champion in Olympic swimming history,<ref>{{cite web |url=https://swimswam.com/michael-phelps-becomes-oldest-win-individual-gold-swimming-medal/ |title=Michael Phelps becomes oldest to win individual gold swimming medal |first1=Robert |last1=Gibbs |date=August 9, 2016 |publisher=Swimswam |access-date=August 10, 2016}}</ref> beating the records set by [[Duke Kahanamoku]] in [[Swimming at the 1920 Summer Olympics – Men's 100 metre freestyle|1920]], and [[Inge de Bruijn]] in [[Swimming at the 2004 Summer Olympics – Women's 50 metre freestyle|2004]] respectively. Phelps also became the first swimmer to win individual gold medals 12 years apart.<ref name="sb">{{cite web |url=https://www.sbnation.com/2016/8/9/12419516/michael-phelps-gold-medal-record-leonidas-of-rhodes |title=Michael Phelps tied a 2,168-year-old Olympic record |first1=Rodger |last1=Sherman |date=August 9, 2016 |publisher=[[SB Nation]] |access-date=August 10, 2016}}</ref> Both these records were broken by [[Anthony Ervin]] three days later.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://swimswam.com/ervin-passes-phelps-become-oldest-swimmer-win-solo-gold/ |title=Ervin passes Phelps to become oldest swimmer to win solo gold |first1=Robert |last1=Gibbs |date=August 12, 2016 |publisher=Swimswam |access-date=August 13, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Rio 2016 Olympic Games - Swimming - Men's 200m Butterfly |url=http://results.nbcolympics.com/swimming/event/men-200m-butterfly/index.html |archive-url=https://archive.today/20160811092019/http://results.nbcolympics.com/swimming/event/men-200m-butterfly/index.html |url-status=dead |archive-date=August 11, 2016 |publisher=NBC News }}</ref>

Also on August 9, Phelps won his 21st gold medal in the [[Swimming at the 2016 Summer Olympics – Men's 4 × 200 metre freestyle relay|4 × 200 m freestyle relay]] together with [[Conor Dwyer]], [[Townley Haas]], and [[Ryan Lochte]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Phelps, Lochte, Dwyer and Haas continue U.S.' golden dominance of 4x200 freestyle relay|publisher=NBC Olympics|date=August 9, 2016|url=http://www.nbcolympics.com/news/phelps-lochte-dwyer-and-haas-continue-us-golden-dominance-4x200m-freestyle-relay|access-date=March 30, 2017}}</ref> For Phelps and Lochte, this was their 4th consecutive gold medal in this event,<ref>{{cite news|last=Svrluga|first=Barry|title=Michael Phelps extends his legacy with two more gold medals at Rio Olympics|work=The Washington Post|date=August 9, 2016|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/sports/olympics/at-rio-games-ryan-lochte-sports-silver-hair-and-an-familiar-title-underdog/2016/08/09/4fa73f04-5e25-11e6-af8e-54aa2e849447_story.html|access-date=March 30, 2017}}</ref> an [[List of multiple Olympic gold medalists in one event#Team events, consecutive titles|all-time record]] in swimming for any event.{{citation needed|date=November 2016}}
[[File:Adrian, Held, Phelps, Dressel Rio 2016.jpg|thumb|260px|left|Phelps with [[Nathan Adrian]], [[Ryan Held]] and [[Caeleb Dressel]], after winning the [[Swimming at the 2016 Summer Olympics – Men's 4 × 100 metre freestyle relay|4 × 100 m freestyle relay]]]]

On August 11, Phelps won his 22nd gold medal in the [[Swimming at the 2016 Summer Olympics – Men's 200 metre individual medley|200 m individual medley]]. He beat [[Kosuke Hagino]], the 400 m individual medley champion, by 1.95 seconds. This was Phelps's 4th consecutive gold medal in the event as well as his 4th in the Games. He became the first swimmer to win the same individual event four times, surpassing the previous record of three held by [[Dawn Fraser]] and [[Krisztina Egerszegi]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://swimswam.com/michael-phelps-wins-record-4th-consecutive-200-im-22nd-career-gold/ |title=Michael Phelps wins record 4th consecutive 200 IM, 22nd career gold |first1=James |last1=Sutherland |date=August 11, 2016 |publisher=Swimswam |access-date=August 12, 2016}}</ref> He also became the third Olympian to [[List of multiple Olympic gold medalists in one event#Individual events|win the same individual event]] four times, after athletes [[Al Oerter]] and [[Carl Lewis]].<ref name="sportscafe" /><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.baltimoresun.com/sports/olympics/bal-michael-phelps-wins-fourth-gold-in-200-im-outdueling-ryan-lochte-for-perhaps-last-time-20160811-story.html |title=Michael Phelps wins fourth gold in 200 IM, outdueling Ryan Lochte for perhaps last time |first1=Childs |last1=Walker |date=August 12, 2016 |work=[[The Baltimore Sun]] |access-date=August 12, 2016}}</ref> With that 13th individual gold medal, Phelps broke a 2,168-year-old [[Ancient Olympic Games|ancient Olympic]] record, set by [[Leonidas of Rhodes]], who had held the most Olympic individual titles of all time, with twelve.<ref name="auto"/><ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2016/08/12/sports/olympics/michael-phelps-200-im-ryan-lochte-leonidas.html |title=Michael Phelps's 13th Individual Gold Breaks an Ancient Record |last1=Mills |first1=Karen Crouse, Doug |date=August 11, 2016 |last2=Lee |first2=Chang W. |newspaper=The New York Times |issn=0362-4331 |access-date=August 12, 2016}}</ref>

In the [[Swimming at the 2016 Summer Olympics – Men's 100 metre butterfly|100 m butterfly]], Phelps was defeated in his last individual event of the Rio Olympics by Singaporean [[Joseph Schooling]], when he earned joint silver along with Chad le Clos and [[László Cseh]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Rio Olympics 2016: Joseph Schooling beats Michael Phelps in 100m butterfly |publisher=BBC |date=August 13, 2016 |url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/olympics/37068610}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Chappell |first1=Bill |title=Michael Phelps Misses Shot at 5th Gold Medal in Rio, Wins Silver in Butterfly |url=https://www.npr.org/sections/thetorch/2016/08/12/489851318/michael-phelps-misses-shot-at-5th-gold-medal-in-rio-wins-silver-in-butterfly |access-date=August 13, 2016 |date=August 12, 2016}}</ref>

On August 13, in the [[Swimming at the 2016 Summer Olympics – Men's 4 × 100 metre medley relay|4 × 100-meter medley relay]], Phelps ended his career with another gold medal, his 23rd at the Olympics and his 28th medal overall. Together with [[Ryan Murphy (swimmer)|Ryan Murphy]], [[Cody Miller]], and [[Nathan Adrian]], swimming as the butterfly leg of the [[Medley swimming|medley]], they broke the Olympic record,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.nbcolympics.com/news/michael-phelps-wins-career-olympic-gold-no-23-medley-relay |title=Michael Phelps wins career Olympic gold No. 23 in medley relay |first1=Rachel |last1=Lutz |date=August 13, 2016 |publisher=[[NBC Olympics]] |access-date=August 14, 2016}}</ref> and won the United States' 1001st [[All-time Olympic Games medal table|all time]] [[United States at the 2016 Summer Olympics|Olympic gold medal]], in accordance with the [[United States Olympic Committee|USOC]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.sbnation.com/2016/8/13/12465416/united-states-olympics-gold-medal-count-history-1000-or-is-it-999 |title=The United States says it has won 1,000 Olympic gold medals, but it may only have 999 |last=Bien |first=Louis |date=August 14, 2016 |publisher=[[SB Nation]] |access-date=August 14, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.sbnation.com/2016/8/13/12469660/olympics-2016-swimming-results-4x100m-medley-relay-mens-gold-united-states |title=Olympic swimming results 2016: Michael Phelps leads U.S. to medley relay gold in his final Olympic race |last=Brady |first=James |date=August 14, 2016 |publisher=[[SB Nation]] |access-date=August 14, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.chicagotribune.com/sports/international/ct-rio-olympics-mens-swimming-4x100m-medley-relay-20160813-story.html |title=Golden finale: Michael Phelps captures his 23rd Olympic gold with relay win |last=Tribune |first=Chicago |access-date=August 14, 2016}}</ref> Phelps retired from competitive swimming again following the Rio Olympics.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cbsnews.com/news/olympic-swimmer-michael-phelps-on-his-next-chapter-after-retirement/|title=Olympic swimmer Michael Phelps on his "new chapter" after retirement|website=CBS News}}</ref>

Phelps's performance in the Rio Olympics was unique in "winning multiple gold medals at 31 years old, well beyond the typical peak for male swimmers". Phelps is considered one of the greatest Olympians of all time.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ft.com/content/5f353a1c-6928-11e6-a0b1-d87a9fea034f|title=Rio Olympics 2016: a visual analysis of Phelps, Biles and Bolt|first=John|last=Burn-Murdoch|date=August 23, 2016|website=Financial Times}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/olympics/37037571|title=Rio Olympics 2016: Phelps, Bolt, Owens - who is the greatest Olympian of all time?|date=August 11, 2016|via=www.bbc.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ibtimes.com/usain-bolt-vs-michael-phelps-whos-greatest-olympian-all-time-2402642|title=Usain Bolt vs. Michael Phelps: Who's The Greatest Olympian Of All Time?|date=August 16, 2016}}</ref>

==Testing for performance-enhancing drugs==
During the 2008 Olympics, Phelps was questioned by the press as to whether perhaps his feats were "too good to be true", a reference to unsupported rumors that Phelps might be taking [[performance-enhancing substance]]s.<ref>Phelps, ''No Limits'', p. 185.</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=I'm clean, says history making Phelps |url=http://www.dnaindia.com/sport/report_i-m-clean-says-history-making-phelps_1183542 |work=Daily News and Analysis |location=India |date=August 15, 2008 |access-date=June 21, 2010}}</ref> In response, Phelps noted that he had signed up for Project Believe, a project by the [[United States Anti-Doping Agency]] in which U.S. Olympians can volunteer to be tested in excess of the [[World Anti-Doping Agency]] guidelines.<ref>{{cite news |title=Michael Phelps shrugs off question of drugs |url=http://www.timesonline.co.uk/tol/sport/olympics/article4537584.ece |work=The Sunday Times |author=Craig Lord |date=July 2, 2008 |access-date=June 21, 2010 |location=London}}</ref> During the Games, Phelps passed all nine tests that were administered to him.<ref>{{cite news|title=Phelps deals with doping questions |url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/archives/article704542.ece |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090822053818/http://www.theglobeandmail.com/archives/article704542.ece |url-status=dead |archive-date=August 22, 2009 |work=The Globe and Mail |location=Canada |author=Allan Maki |date=August 15, 2008 |access-date=June 21, 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=So Far, Drug Testing Has Revealed Only a Few Positives |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2008/08/16/sports/olympics/16doping.html |work=The New York Times |author=Gina Kolata |date=August 15, 2008 |access-date=June 21, 2010}}</ref>

==Training==
Phelps has trained under [[Bob Bowman (coach)|Bob Bowman]] since he was 11 years old.<ref>Schaller, p. 24.</ref> Bowman swam for [[Florida State University]] from 1983 to 1985.<ref>Schaller, p. 22.</ref> Phelps has said Bowman reminded him of a [[Drill instructor|drill sergeant]] because of his disciplined and regimented ways.<ref>Schaller, p. 25.</ref> However, Phelps has said, "Training with Bob is the smartest thing I've ever done ... I'm not going to swim for anyone else."<ref>{{cite news |title=Opposites attract |url=http://www.baltimoresun.com/sports/bal-te.sp.bowman16aug16,0,265609.story |work=The Baltimore Sun |author=Kevin Van Valkenburg |date=August 16, 2008 |access-date=July 3, 2010}}</ref> After the 2004 Summer Olympics, Bowman was hired as the head coach for the [[University of Michigan]] after [[Jon Urbanchek]] retired. Phelps joined Bowman at Michigan to train and attended classes, but did not pursue a degree.<ref>Schaller, p. 45.</ref><ref>Schaller, p. 66.</ref> Phelps served as a volunteer assistant coach at Michigan.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.mgoblue.com/sports/olympics/spec-rel/2012-olympics-roster.html |title=University of Michigan Official Athletic Site – Olympics |publisher=Mgoblue.Com |date=July 26, 2012 |access-date=August 1, 2012 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120801041050/http://www.mgoblue.com/sports/olympics/spec-rel/2012-olympics-roster.html |archive-date=August 1, 2012  }}</ref> After the 2008 Summer Olympics, Bowman returned to Baltimore as CEO at the [[North Baltimore Aquatic Club]]. Phelps also returned to Baltimore with Bowman.<ref>Schaller, p. 27.</ref> When Bowman was hired as the men's and women's swimming coach at [[Arizona State University]] in 2015, Phelps moved to Arizona to continue training under Bowman.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.baltimoresun.com/sports/olympics/bs-sp-digest-0515-20150515-story.html|title=Michael Phelps on moving to Arizona: 'I get to be tan all year'|date=May 15, 2015|website=The Baltimore Sun|access-date=August 7, 2017}}</ref> There is a popular myth that Phelps ate 12,000 calories every day, but Phelps has stated it has been exaggerated and that he did not eat so much even in his growing days.<ref name="eisenband">{{cite news |last1=Eisenband |first1=Jeff |title=Michael Phelps Debunks Myth Of His 12,000-Calorie Diet |url=http://www.thepostgame.com/michael-phelps-debunks-12000-calorie-diet-myth |access-date=December 17, 2019 |publisher=The Post Game |date=June 16, 2017}}</ref><ref name="jennings">{{cite web |last1=Jennings |first1=Ken |title=The Debunker: Did Michael Phelps Really Eat 12,000 Calories a Day? |url=https://www.woot.com/blog/post/the-debunker-did-michael-phelps-really-eat-12-000-calories-a-day |website=woot.com |publisher=Woot |date=June 12, 2019 |access-date=December 17, 2019}}</ref>

==Personal life==
[[File:Michael Phelps & Nicole Johnson by Gage Skidmore.jpg|thumb|right|Phelps with his wife, Nicole Johnson]]
Bob Bowman described Phelps as "a solitary man"<ref name="Phelps life">{{cite news |title=Profile: Michael Phelps |url=http://www.timesonline.co.uk/tol/sport/olympics/article4547306.ece |newspaper=The Sunday Times |date=August 17, 2008 |archive-url=https://archive.today/20100907191225/http://www.timesonline.co.uk/tol/sport/olympics/article4547306.ece |archive-date=September 7, 2010 |access-date=September 7, 2010 |location=London |url-status=dead  }}</ref> with a "rigid focus"<ref name="voyage" /> at the pool prior to a race, but afterward "a man incredibly invested in the success of the people he cares about".<ref name="voyage" /> He states that "he's unbelievably kind-hearted",<ref name="Phelps life" /> recounting Phelps's interaction with young children after practices.<ref name="voyage" />

Phelps is married to former [[Miss California USA]] [[Nicole Johnson (Miss California USA)|Nicole Johnson]]. They secretly married on June 13, 2016, and the marriage was not publicly reported until four months later.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://abcnews.go.com/Entertainment/michael-phelps-married-nicole-johnson/story?id=43087505 |title=Michael Phelps Is Married to Nicole Johnson |first=Lesley |last=Messer |date=October 26, 2016 |website=[[ABC News]] |access-date=October 27, 2016}}</ref> They met in 2007 at the [[ESPY Award|ESPYs]], broke up in 2012, reconciled, and got engaged in February 2015.<ref name=engaged>{{cite web |url=http://time.com/3717812/michael-phelps-engaged/ |title=Michael Phelps Just Got Engaged to Former Miss California USA |work=[[Time (magazine)|Time]] |date=February 22, 2015 |access-date=February 22, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2016/08/08/sports/olympics/michael-phelps-swimming-rio-2016-relishes-new-reality.html?_r=0 |title=Michael Phelps Relishes the Cheer and Challenge of His New Reality |newspaper=The New York Times |date=August 7, 2016 |access-date=August 14, 2016}}</ref> They have three sons, Boomer Robert Phelps, born on May 5, 2016,<ref>{{cite web |last1=Park |first1=Andrea |title=Michael Phelps Welcomes Son Boomer: 'Best Feeling I Have Ever Felt in My Life' |url=http://celebritybabies.people.com/2016/05/07/michael-phelps-welcomes-son-boomer-baby/?xid=socialflow_facebook_peoplemag |website=People Babies |date=May 7, 2016}}</ref> Beckett Richard Phelps, born on February 12, 2018,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.huffingtonpost.com/entry/michael-phelps-wife-nicole-second-son-beckett_us_5a8447ffe4b02b66c51403e8|title=Michael Phelps And Wife Nicole Welcome Second Son, Beckett|work=[[Huffington Post]]|date=February 14, 2018}}</ref> and Maverick Nicolas Phelps, born on September 9, 2019.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://swimswam.com/phelps-baby-no-3-michael-and-nicole-welcome-3rd-son-maverick/|title=Phelps baby No. 3: Michael and Nicole welcome 3rd son, Maverick|work=Swimswam.com|date=September 11, 2019}}</ref> The family lives in [[Paradise Valley, Arizona]], an affluent town adjoined to Phoenix, where Phelps volunteers alongside Bowman as an assistant coach for the [[Arizona State Sun Devils]] swim team.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://azcentral.com/story/money/real-estate/catherine-reagor/2016/08/22/solid-gold-inside-michael-phelps-paradise-valley-home/89123120/|title=Solid gold: Inside Michael Phelps' Paradise Valley home|last=Reagor|first=Catherine|date=August 22, 2016|website=AZCentral|access-date=August 7, 2017}}</ref>

As a teenager, Phelps idolized Australian swimmer [[Ian Thorpe]] and modeled his public image after Thorpe.<ref>Phelps, ''Beneath the Surface'', p. 95.</ref> Thorpe initially said that it would be highly unlikely for Phelps to win eight gold medals at the [[2008 Summer Olympics]] in Beijing.<ref>{{cite news |title=Thorpe's doubt of eight gold sweep spurs Phelps |url=http://www.theaustralian.com.au/news/thorpes-doubt-of-eight-gold-sweep-spurs-phelps/story-e6frg7mo-1111116988410 |work=The Australian |author=Nicole Jeffery |date=July 23, 2008 |access-date=June 21, 2010}}</ref> Phelps used the remarks as motivation and taped the words to his locker during the Games.<ref>Phelps, ''Beneath the Surface'', p. 281.</ref> Thorpe was in the stands for the [[Swimming at the 2008 Summer Olympics – Men's 4 × 100 metre medley relay|4×100-meter medley relay]], where Phelps was swimming for his eighth Olympic gold medal. When Phelps and his teammates captured the gold, Thorpe gave a congratulatory kiss to Phelps's mother, then gave a handshake and a hug to congratulate Phelps. Afterwards, Thorpe said "I'm really proud of him not just because he won eight golds. Rather, it's how much he has grown up and matured into a great human being. Never in my life have I been so happy to have been proved wrong."<ref name="Phelps, No Limits, p. 218"/><ref>{{cite news |title=Ian Thorpe happy to have been proved wrong by Michael Phelps |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/othersports/olympics/2591815/Ian-Thorpe-happy-to-have-been-proved-wrong-by-Michael-Phelps-Olympics.html |archive-url=https://wayback.archive-it.org/all/20140206125854/http://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/olympics/2591815/Ian-Thorpe-happy-to-have-been-proved-wrong-by-Michael-Phelps-Olympics.html |url-status=dead |archive-date=February 6, 2014 |work=The Daily Telegraph |author=Kaz Mochlinski |date=August 20, 2008 |access-date=June 21, 2010 |location=London}}</ref>

Phelps has also cited [[Michael Jordan]] as a sporting idol of his, and stated that "he changed the sport of basketball".<ref>https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=lE1ZIZqBa9s</ref> Phelps is also a fan of the [[Baltimore Ravens]] and stated that he found his life purpose and desire to compete in the [[2016 Summer Olympics]] after seeking [[Ray Lewis]]'s advice.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.baltimoresun.com/sports/baltimore-sports-blog/bal-ray-lewis-tweets-strange-thing-about-michael-phelps-medal-count-deletes-it-20160810-story.html|title=Ray Lewis tweets strange thing about Michael Phelps' medal count, deletes it|last=Shaffer|first=Jonas|date=August 10, 2016|publisher=The Baltimore Sun|access-date=September 9, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://qpolitical.com/1-nearly-dying-michael-phelps-tells-god-saved-life-made-swim/|title=After Nearly Dying, Michael Phelps Admits The Secret That Saved His Life And Made Him Swim Again|date=August 5, 2016|publisher=qpolitical.com|access-date=September 9, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160916202905/http://qpolitical.com/1-nearly-dying-michael-phelps-tells-god-saved-life-made-swim/|archive-date=September 16, 2016|url-status=dead}}</ref>

In January 2018, Phelps revealed that he has struggled both with [[Attention deficit hyperactivity disorder|ADHD]] and [[Major depressive disorder|depression]], having contemplated [[suicide]] after the 2012 Olympics.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://people.com/sports/michael-phelps-opens-up-about-adhd-struggles-in-new-video-a-teacher-told-me-id-never-amount-to-anything/|title=Michael Phelps Opens Up About ADHD Struggles: A Teacher Told Me 'I'd Never Amount to Anything'|website=PEOPLE}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://people.com/sports/michael-phelps-thought-about-suicide/|title=Michael Phelps Says He Contemplated Suicide After 2012 Olympics|website=PEOPLE}}</ref>

==Legal issues==
At age 19 in November 2004, Phelps was arrested for [[driving under the influence of alcohol]] in [[Salisbury, Maryland]].<ref>Schaller, p. 42.</ref> He pleaded guilty to [[driving while impaired]] and was sentenced to serve 18 months of [[probation]], fined $250, ordered to speak to high school students about drinking and driving, and to attend a [[Mothers Against Drunk Driving]] (MADD) meeting.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.cbsnews.com/stories/2004/11/08/national/main654380.shtml |title=Olympic Champ Sentenced For DUI |publisher=CBS News |date=December 29, 2004 |access-date=February 14, 2008}}</ref> When Phelps was later asked about the incident by [[Matt Lauer]] on the [[Today (NBC program)|''Today Show'']], he said that he had "let a lot of people in the country down".<ref name="voyage" />

In February 2009, a photograph of Phelps using a [[bong]] went viral; this resulted in the loss of the [[Kellogg Company]] as a sponsor, as well as a three-month suspension by [[USA Swimming]]. Phelps admitted that the photo, which was taken at a party at the [[University of South Carolina]], was authentic. He publicly apologized, saying his behavior was "inappropriate".<ref>{{cite news |title=Phelps Disciplined Over Marijuana Pipe Incident |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2009/02/06/sports/othersports/06phelps.html?ref=sports |work=The New York Times |first=Juliet |last=Macur |date=February 5, 2009 |access-date=February 5, 2009}}</ref>

In September 2014, Phelps was arrested again, this time on charges of driving under the influence of alcohol and speeding in [[Baltimore]].<ref>[https://news.yahoo.com/olympian-michael-phelps-arrested-dui-charge-170245539.html Olympian Michael Phelps apologizes for DUI arrest], [[Associated Press]], September 30, 2014.</ref> As a result, USA Swimming suspended him from all competitions for six months, and stated he would not be chosen to represent the United States at the [[2015 World Aquatics Championships]] in August.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/swimming/29515422 |title=Michael Phelps suspended from swimming for six months |work=BBC News |date=October 6, 2014 |access-date=October 6, 2014}}</ref> With Phelps off the team, the United States failed to qualify for the finals of the 4 × 100 m freestyle relay.<ref name="nbcolympics.com"/>

==Philanthropy==
{{multiple image
| align = left
