After the 2008 Olympics, Phelps used his $1&nbsp;million [[Speedo]] bonus to set up the Michael Phelps Foundation.<ref>Phelps, ''No Limits'', p. 227.</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Phelps to use $1&nbsp;million bonus to start charity |url=http://today.msnbc.msn.com/id/26506320/ |publisher=TODAY People |author=Bob Considine |date=September 2, 2008 |access-date=June 21, 2010 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100728125731/http://today.msnbc.msn.com/id/26506320 |archive-date=July 28, 2010  }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last=Johnson |first=Drew |title=Michael Phelps Launches Foundation, Donates Speedo $1 Million Bonus to Charity Olympic Gold Medalist Embarks on Eight-City Tour |url=http://www.warnaco.com/content/speedousa.com/20080902/20080902_mp.html |access-date=May 30, 2012 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120415073619/http://www.warnaco.com/content/speedousa.com/20080902/20080902_mp.html |archive-date=April 15, 2012  }}</ref> His foundation focuses on growing the sport of swimming and promoting healthier lifestyles.<ref>Phelps, ''No Limits'', p. 226.</ref>

In 2010, the Michael Phelps Foundation, the Michael Phelps Swim School and [[KidsHealth]].org developed and nationally piloted the "im" program for [[Boys & Girls Clubs of America|Boys & Girls Club]] members. The im program teaches children the importance of being active and healthy, with a focus on the sport of swimming. It also promotes the value of planning and goal-setting.<ref name=valkenburg>{{cite news |last=Van Valkenburg |first=Kevin |title=Phelps expands swimming education initiative |url=http://www.baltimoresun.com/sports/bs-sp-phelps-foundation-0624-20110623,0,136720.story |newspaper=[[The Baltimore Sun]] |access-date=August 8, 2012 |date=June 24, 2011}}</ref> ''im'' is offered through the Boys & Girls Clubs of America<ref name=valkenburg /> and through [[Special Olympics]] International.<ref>{{cite news |last=Murphy |first=Mandy |title=Michael Phelps Becomes Special Olympics' Newest Global Ambassador |url=http://www.specialolympics.org/Press/2011/Michael_Phelps_Becomes_Special_Olympics_Global_Ambassador.aspx# |access-date=May 30, 2012 |date=August 1, 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120419150107/http://www.specialolympics.org/Press/2011/Michael_Phelps_Becomes_Special_Olympics_Global_Ambassador.aspx |archive-date=April 19, 2012 |url-status=dead  }}</ref> The Foundation has since developed two other programs, Level Field Fund-Swimming and Caps-for-a-Cause.<ref>{{cite web|last=Michael Phelps Foundation |title=Programs |url=http://michaelphelpsfoundation.org/the_foundation.php |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120305035714/http://www.michaelphelpsfoundation.org/the_foundation.php |url-status=dead |archive-date=March 5, 2012 |publisher=Michael Phelps Foundation |access-date=May 30, 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Level Field Fund Establishes Level Field Fund – Swimming |url=http://www.levelfieldfund.org/level-field-fund-establishes-level-field-fund-%E2%80%93-swimming |access-date=May 30, 2012 |date=August 16, 2010}}</ref>

The Foundation's largest event is its annual fundraiser, the Michael Phelps Foundation Golf Classic.<ref>{{cite news |last=Van Valkenburg |first=Kevin |title=Tee times, not London, keeping Phelps busy |url=http://articles.baltimoresun.com/2010-09-14/sports/bs-sp-phelps-0914-20100913_1_bob-bowman-michael-phelps-promising-swimmers |access-date=May 30, 2012 |newspaper=The Baltimore Sun |date=September 14, 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last=Phelps |first=Michael |title=Michael Phelps Foundation Golf Classic |url=http://paceclub.speedousa.com/athletes/blog_posts/michael-phelps-foundation-golf-classic |publisher=Speedo Pace Club |access-date=May 30, 2012 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120119120338/http://paceclub.speedousa.com/athletes/blog_posts/michael-phelps-foundation-golf-classic |archive-date=January 19, 2012  }}</ref> Phelps stated he hoped to work with his Foundation more after retirement from competition following the [[2012 Summer Olympics]] in London.<ref>{{cite news |last=Schultz |first=Jordan |title=Michael Phelps on London 2012 Olympics, His New Post-Swimming Diet And Retirement Plans |url=https://huffingtonpost.com/2012/05/11/michael-phelps-on-london-olympics_n_1499884.html |access-date=May 30, 2012 |work=The Huffington Post |date=May 11, 2012}}</ref>

In 2017, Phelps joined the board of [[Medibio Limited|Medibio]], a company focused on diagnosis of mental health disorders.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://medibio.com.au/board-of-directors/|title=Our Company|work=Medibio|access-date=July 5, 2017|language=en-AU}}</ref>
{{clear}}

==Honors and awards==
[[File:Phelps and Busch 2009.jpg|thumb|right|Phelps and Maryland House Speaker [[Michael E. Busch|Mike Busch]] in April 2009. Both houses of the [[Maryland General Assembly]] honored Phelps that day.]]
Phelps was a USA Olympic team member in 2000, 2004, 2008, 2012 and 2016, and holds the records for most Olympic gold medals (23), most such medals in individual events (13), and most such medals at a single games (8, in Beijing 2008).<ref name="phelpsbio">{{Cite news |publisher=USA Swimming |title=USA Swimming bio: Michael Phelps |url=https://www.usaswimming.org/DesktopModules/BioViewManaged.aspx?personid=4beec290-d7ae-483d-a512-36b18a4e022a&TabId=1453&Mid=10312 |access-date=August 25, 2010 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120405075041/http://www.usaswimming.org/DesktopModules/BioViewManaged.aspx?personid=4beec290-d7ae-483d-a512-36b18a4e022a&TabId=1453&Mid=10312 |archive-date=April 5, 2012  }}</ref> A street in his hometown of Baltimore was renamed The Michael Phelps Way in 2004.<ref>{{cite news |title=Athlete Bio: Michael Phelps |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2008/07/26/sports/olympics/biophelps.html |newspaper=The New York Times |date=July 26, 2008 |archive-url=https://archive.today/20120905022741/http://www.nytimes.com/2008/07/26/sports/olympics/biophelps.html?_r=1 |archive-date=September 5, 2012 |access-date=September 5, 2010 |url-status=dead}}</ref> On April 9, 2009, Phelps was invited to appear before the [[Maryland House of Delegates]] and the [[Maryland Senate]], to be honored for his Olympic accomplishments.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://weblogs.baltimoresun.com/news/local/politics/2009/04/michael_phelps_general_assembl.html |title=Phelps wins over General Assembly, hopes Preakness stays in Maryland |work=The Baltimore Sun |access-date=April 11, 2009}}</ref>

Phelps has also received the following awards:
* ''[[Swimming World]]'' [[World Swimmer of the Year Award]]: 2003, 2004, 2006, 2007, 2008, 2009, 2012,<ref name="Swimming World Awards">{{cite news |title=Swimming World Magazine: Swimmers of the Year |url=http://www.swimmingworldmagazine.com/SwimmersOfTheYear.asp |work=Swimming World |access-date=December 1, 2016}}</ref> 2016<ref name="Swimming World Awards 2016">{{cite news |title=Swimming World Magazine Announces World and American Swimmers of the Year |url=https://www.swimmingworldmagazine.com/news/swimming-world-magazine-announces-world-and-american-swimmers-of-the-year/ |work=Swimming World |date=December 1, 2016 |access-date=December 1, 2016}}</ref>
* ''Swimming World'' [[American Swimmer of the Year Award]]: 2001, 2002, 2003, 2004, 2006, 2007, 2008, 2009, 2012, 2015,<ref name="Swimming World Awards" /><ref>{{cite news |title=Swimming World Names 2009 American Swimmers of the Year |url=http://www.swimmingworldmagazine.com/lane9/news/22830.asp |work=Swimming World |date=November 29, 2009 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110104090125/http://www.swimmingworldmagazine.com/lane9/news/22830.asp |archive-date=January 4, 2011 |access-date=September 5, 2010 |url-status=dead  }}</ref> 2016<ref name="Swimming World Awards 2016" />
* [[Fédération internationale de natation]] [[List of FINA Athletes of the Year|swimmer of the year]] (since 2010): 2012, 2016
* [[Golden Goggle Awards|Golden Goggle]] Male Performance of the Year (since 2004): 2004, 2006, 2007, 2008, 2009,<ref name="phelpsbio"/> 2016<ref name="gg2016">{{cite web |url=http://www.teamusa.org/News/2016/November/22/Michael-Phelps-Katie-Ledecky-Win-Big-At-Golden-Goggle-Awards-As-Team-USA-Celebrates-Rio-Success |title=Michael Phelps, Katie Ledecky Win Big At Golden Goggle Awards As Team USA Celebrates Rio Success |first1=Nick |last1=McCarvel |date=November 22, 2016 |publisher=Team USA |access-date=November 23, 2016 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161124025127/http://www.teamusa.org/News/2016/November/22/Michael-Phelps-Katie-Ledecky-Win-Big-At-Golden-Goggle-Awards-As-Team-USA-Celebrates-Rio-Success |archive-date=November 24, 2016  }}</ref>
* Golden Goggle Relay Performance of the Year (since 2004): 2006, 2007, 2008, 2009,<ref name="phelpsbio"/> 2016<ref name="gg2016" />
* Golden Goggle Male Athlete of the Year (since 2004): 2004, 2007, 2008, 2012, 2014,<ref name="phelpsbio"/> 2015,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.centredaily.com/entertainment/celebrities/article45987195.html |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151124150442/http://www.centredaily.com/entertainment/celebrities/article45987195.html |url-status=dead |archive-date=November 24, 2015 |title=Ledecky wins 3 trophies; Phelps earns 1 at Golden Goggles |first1=Beth |last1=Harris |date=November 23, 2015 |work=[[Centre Daily Times]] |access-date=November 25, 2015}}</ref> 2016<ref name="gg2016" />
* Golden Goggle Impact award: 2016<ref name="gg2016" />
* [[SwimSwam]] [[Swammy Awards|Swammy Award]] for Male Swimmer of the Year: 2016<ref>Neidigh, Lauren, [https://swimswam.com/2016-swammy-awards-male-swimmer-year-michael-phelps/ 2016 Swammy Awards: Male Swimmer of the Year Michael Phelps]. December 31, 2016</ref>
* [[USOC Athlete of the Year|USOC SportsMan of the Year Award]]: 2004, 2008,<ref>{{cite news|title=USOC Athletes of the Year |url=http://www.teamusa.org/resources/olympic-facts-figures/olympic-honors/usoc-athletes-of-the-year |archive-url=https://wayback.archive-it.org/all/20100216074339/http://www.teamusa.org/resources/olympic-facts-figures/olympic-honors/usoc-athletes-of-the-year |url-status=dead |archive-date=February 16, 2010 |publisher=United States Olympic Committee |access-date=September 5, 2010}}</ref> 2011–12,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.abs-cbnnews.com/sports/09/18/12/phelps-and-felix-win-top-us-olympic-athlete-awards |title=Phelps and Felix win top US Olympic athlete awards |agency=Reuters}}</ref> 2016<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.teamusa.org/News/2016/September/28/US-Olympic-Committee-Announces-2016-Winners-For-Team-USA-Awards-Presented-By-Dow-Best-Of-The-Games |title=U.S. Olympic Committee Announces 2016 Winners For Team USA Awards Presented By Dow, Best Of The Games |date=September 28, 2016 |publisher=Team USA |access-date=September 30, 2016}}</ref>
* [[James E. Sullivan Award]]: 2003<ref>{{cite news |title=Phelps joins prestigious Sullivan list |last=Freeman |first=Rick |url=https://www.usatoday.com/sports/olympics/2004-04-13-sullivan-award-phelps_x.htm |newspaper=USA Today |agency=Associated Press |date=April 13, 2004 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110604114730/http://www.usatoday.com/sports/olympics/2004-04-13-sullivan-award-phelps_x.htm |archive-date=June 4, 2011 |access-date=September 5, 2010 |url-status=dead  }}</ref>
